Recap:
The Toronto Raptors defeated the Milwaukee Bucks, 118-93, in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs at Air Canada Center on Monday. 

This series has been competitive throughout, but this was a lopsided result in Toronto's favor. In fact, the Raptors led by 11 after the first quarter and the game never got within seven points from there. In addition, Toronto held a double-digit lead for the final 21 minutes. This was the Raptors best offensive performance of the series, as they shot 58 percent from the field, 44 percent from three-point range and 92 percent from the free-throw line. They also dominated the rebounding, winning that battle, 40-23.

The Bucks (2-3) simply dug themselves too big of a hole in this game, as they'll now have to win out to advance to the second-round. Giannis Antetokounmpo was a bright spot for Milwaukee, as he collected 30 points, nine rebounds, three assists, three steals and three blocks. Malcolm Brogdon was the only other starter in double figures, totaling 19 points, two rebounds and three assists. Khris Middleton accumulated eight points, three rebounds, six assists and five steals. Greg Monroe led the bench with 11 points, two rebounds and two assists.

The Raptors (3-2) are now just one win away from a berth in the second-round, as this was one of their best performances of the postseason thus far. Norman Powell got another start and provided 25 points, four rebounds, four assists and three steals on 8-of-11 shooting. DeMar DeRozan amassed 18 points, three rebounds and six assists. Serge Ibaka finished with 19 points, six rebounds, three assists and three blocks. Kyle Lowry recorded a double-double, accruing 16 points, three rebounds, 10 assists and three steals.

Game 6 will be in Milwaukee on Thursday,

The host Atlanta Hawks took down the Washington Wizards, 111-101, in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs at Philips Arena on Monday.  

The Hawks (2-2) have bounced back from a two-game hole, evening up the series with Monday's win.  It was a solid team effort to earn the win, as seven players scored in double figures.  Atlanta was the first team to achieve that feat in the 2017 playoffs.  The team was primarily led by veteran center Dwight Howard, who had a whopping 16-point, 15-rebound double-double.  Howard connected on a number of alley-oops, helping to swing momentum in Atlanta's favor.  All-Star forward Paul Millsap, who led the team to victory in Game 3, added a team-high 19 points along with nine rebounds and seven assists.  The Hawks will hope to keep momentum from their win as they leave their home court for Game 5.

Washington (2-2), meanwhile, has lost some of its momentum after dropping both games in Atlanta.  Many pegged Game 3's loss on a sub-par performance from star shooting guard Bradley Beal, but Beal bounced back nicely on Monday.  He led the team with 32 points, including five of the team's 11 three-pointers.  All-Star point guard John Wall also made a stellar contribution, scoring 22 point while dishing out a team-high 10 assists.  Wall did, however, have six turnovers, including two down the stretch as the Wizards attempted to come back.  

Game 5 will be in Washington on Wednesday.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the Portland Trail Blazers 128-103 in Monday's Game 4 of their first-round playoff series at Moda Center. 

It didn't take long for Monday's contest to get out of hand, as just three and a half minutes into the game, the Warriors (4-0) had opened up a 14-0 lead and ultimately jumped out to a 28-5 lead over the first six minutes of the first quarter. From there, the Trail Blazers (0-4) struggled to get much closer, with Golden State set on ending this series on Monday night. Despite playing in just three quarters, Steph Curry was sensational, scoring a game-high 37 points in just 30 minutes while shooting 7-of-11 from behind the arc. Draymond Green was the only Warriors player who played more than 30 minutes, and in that time, he shot 7-of-11 from the field, scored 21 points, grabbed six rebounds, dished out four assists and blocked three shots. In the end, six different Golden State players scored in double figures as the team shot a scorching 53.5 percent from the field 58.6 percent from behind the arc. 

As for Portland, the same could not be said, as they shot a miserable 38.3 percent from the field overall in the 25-point loss. Despite the ugly game, Damian Lillard was still terrific, scoring a team-high 34 points on 12-of-24 shooting from the field in 41 minutes. His partner in the backcourt, C.J. McCollum, however, was not so terrific. McCollum capped off the first-round series with a 2-of-12 shooting performance from the field that led to him scoring just six points, and through three quarters, the shooting guard had been 0-of-9 from the field. Al-Farouq Aminu wound up putting together a solid performance, scoring 25 points in 35 minutes off the bench to go along with seven rebounds and two steals.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the Indiana Pacers, 106-102, in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Sunday. 

Cleveland have been dominant all series and a sweep is just what they need to get some rest for the second-round. This game was close much like the rest of the series, as there were seven ties and five lead changes in total, with neither team leading by more than 13 points. The middle quarters were key, with Cleveland outscoring Indiana, 66-53, in the second and third quarters. Free-throw shooting was also huge, with the Cavaliers hitting 23-of-27 from the free-throw line and the Pacers going just 10-of-17. Cleveland also won the rebounding differential, 48-42.

The Cavaliers (4-0) looked lost headed into the postseason, but a first-round series sweep would indicate otherwise. LeBron James was once again the player of the game, as he collected 33 points, 10 rebounds, four assists, four steals and two blocks. Kyrie Irving tallied 28 points, two rebounds and three blocks. Kevin Love scored just five points on 2-of-13 shooting, but snatched down a game-high 16 rebounds. Deron Williams led the bench with 14 points on 4-of-4 from the field.

The Pacers (0-4) simply didn't have enough to compete with the champs and it was evident by this quick postseason exit. Lance Stephenson led Indiana, as he contributed 22 points, six rebounds and three assists off the bench. Paul George accumulated 15 points, seven rebounds, six assists and four steals. Myles Turner amassed 20 points and nine rebounds. Jeff Teague accrued 15 points, four rebounds, 10 assists, two steals and three blocks. Thaddeus Young recorded a double-double, scoring 13 points and grabbing 10 boards.

Cleveland will wait for the Atlanta-Washington series to end to see who they play in the second-round.

The Houston Rockets defeated the host Oklahoma City Thunder, 113-109, in Game 4 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Sunday.

Despite there being just five ties and six lead changes in this game, it was close throughout. In fact, it was a single-digit margin for the final 20 minutes with an extremely hectic finish. That's evident by the fact that there were nine combined steals and fouls in the final 90 seconds. The key for the Rockets was bench production, as they got 64 points and 25 rebounds from their three bench players, while the Thunder's five bench players combined for just 22 points and nine rebounds. Free-throw shooting was also huge, with Houston hitting 28-of-33 and Oklahoma City going just 18-of-32 from the charity stripe.

The Rockets (3-1) now have a commanding 3-1 series lead, as they are headed back home to try to end this series. Nene Hilario was the player of the game, as he provided 28 points and 10 rebounds on a perfect 12-of-12 shooting off the bench. Eric Gordon and Lou Williams were also spectacular off the bench, scoring 18 points a piece, while combing for 15 rebounds. James Harden collected 16 points, seven rebounds and eight assists, but committed seven turnovers on 5-of-16 from the field. Trevor Ariza totaled 14 points, five rebounds, three assists and three steals. 

The Thunder (1-3) needed this win desperately with a 2-1 series deficit, but fell just shy in their home building. Russell Westbrook recorded another triple-double though, accumulating 35 points, 14 rebounds, 14 assists and three steals. Steven Adams amassed 18 points, seven rebounds, two assists and three blocks on 8-of-10 shooting. Victor Oladipo finished with 15 points, four rebounds, two assists, two steals and two blocks. Andre Roberson went just 2-of-12 from the free-throw line, but still accrued 13 points, four rebounds, two steals and five blocks.

Game 5 will be in Houston on Tuesday.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Chicago Bulls, 104-95, at United Center on Sunday evening in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs. The series is now tied 2-2.

The Celtics (2-2) had secured a likely series-salvaging victory on Friday evening, producing a dominating defensive performance in Game 3 at United Center. However, that was only half the battle, as Boston essentially needed to duplicate the same caliber of effort in Game 4 to ensure that they could head back to TD Garden with a deadlocked series. Isaiah Thomas and the defense were successfully able to generate an encore, with the star point guard scoring a game-high 33 points and supplementing them with seven assists, four rebounds and one steal, and Boston limiting the Bulls (2-2) to a 42.1 percent success rate from the field and 20.8 percent from three-point range.

Gerald Green drew another start -- a move by coach Brad Stevens that's proven prudent thus far -- and followed Thomas with 18 points and seven rebounds. Al Horford posted a 15-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included four assists, one steal and one block. Jae Crowder totaled 11 points, two rebounds, one assist and two steals. Kelly Olynyk led the bench with 10 points, three rebounds, one steal and one block.

Jimmy Butler matched Thomas shot for shot, pouring in 33 points and adding nine assists, five rebounds and one steal. Nikola Mirotic was a distant second with 13 points, seven rebounds, one assist and one steal. Isaiah Canaan led the bench by matching Mirotic's scoring total and also providing three assists, two rebounds and two steals. Dwyane Wade turned in 11 points, six boards, two assists, two blocks and one steal. Robin Lopez supplied eight points, seven boards and one block.

The series now shifts back to Boston, where Game 5 will unfold on Wednesday night.

The host Utah Jazz took down the Los Angeles Clippers, 105-98, in Game 4 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Sunday.

Utah (2-2) saw its star big man, Rudy Gobert, return from a knee injury on Sunday.  After going down on the first possession of the series, many expected that the Jazz would be forced to go without Gobert for the duration of the series.  The French big man came back for a stellar showing on Sunday, however, as he delivered 15 points and 13 rebounds in just 24 minutes of play.  Gobert's return to the court was much-needed, as the Jazz were able to see only 10 minutes from All-Star forward Gordon Hayward.  Hayward left Sunday's playoff action due to food poisoning, according to team officials.  

Despite the lack of health for the team, Utah was able to earn its first home playoff victory since 2010.  One of the key factors for the Jazz was veteran wing Joe Johnson.  After hitting the game-winner in Utah's first victory last week, Johnson stepped up in Hayward's absence to deliver a team-high 28 points on 12-of-17 shooting.  Power forward Derrick Favors also made a big impact, shooting 7-of-10 for 17 points in just 24 minutes of action.

Los Angeles (2-2) has had its own fair share of bad luck.  A toe injury in Game 3 wound up putting an end to All-Star forward Blake Griffin's playoff campaign.  The Clippers still have their fair share of star power, however, with superstar Chris Paul continuing to step up in the playoffs.  Paul neared a triple-double on Sunday, scoring a team-high 27 points to go along with 12 assists and nine rebounds.  Sixth man Jamal Crawford, meanwhile, added 25 off the bench.  Griffin's absence stung for the Clippers, however, as rebounding was a major factor throughout.  Utah held a 42-31 advantage on the boards in the game.  

Game 5 will take place back in Los Angeles on Tuesday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Milwaukee Bucks, 87-76, at BMO Harris Bradley Center on Saturday afternoon in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs. The series is now tied 2-2.

Following a 104-77 drubbing in Game 3, the Raptors (2-2), and particularly DeMar DeRozan, had plenty of soul searching to do. Toronto was thoroughly dominated by the Bucks (2-2) defense, while the All-Star shooting guard had gone 0-for-8 from the floor and scored a series-low eight points. Whatever adjustments the Raptors made during their off-day Friday seems to have worked like a charm, as their defense gave plenty of what they got in Game 3, while DeRozan led all scorers with 33 points on 12-of-22 shooting. He added nine rebounds, five assists and four steals over his 40 minutes, doing a pretty fair impression of Milwaukee superstar Giannis Antetokounmpo in the process. It was a thoroughly dominating performance on the defensive end as well, as the Bucks managed success rates of just 37.0 percent from the floor and 23.8 percent from three-point range while being forced into 20 turnovers.

Kyle Lowry followed his backcourt mate with 18 points, four rebounds, four assists, one steal and one block over a game-high 43 minutes. Norman Powell drew the start and posted 12 points, four rebounds, four assists and one block. Serge Ibaka started at center in a lineup shakeup and totaled 10 points, eight rebounds, one assist, three blocks and two steals. Jonas Valancinuas moved to the bench and led the second unit with 12 points, five rebounds and one steal. 

Tony Snell paced the Bucks with 19 points and four rebounds. Antetokounmpo provided 14 points, nine rebounds, four assists, two steals and two blocks. Greg Monroe matched Antetoknunmpo's scoring total and added nine rebounds, one assist, two steals and one block while leading the second unit. Khris Middleton posted a 10-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included three assists and one steal. Thon Maker filled out the stat sheet with seven points, four rebounds, two assists and two steals.

The two teams reconvene for a pivotal Game 5 on Monday night at the Air Canada Centre in Toronto.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the visiting Washington Wizards, 116-98, in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs, at Philips Arena on Saturday evening, The Wizards lead the series 2-1. 

The Hawks started the game with a 19-4 run over the first six minutes and pushed the deficit up to 25, before finishing the first quarter up 38-20. They played solid defense at home, holding the Wizards to only 41.6 percent from the field, including 24.1 percent from long range, and maintained their lead throughout the game. The Hawks dominated the paint, where they out-scored the Wizards, 60-34. 

Paul Millsap was huge for Atlanta, as he led the way with 29 points on 12-of-20 shooting, 14 rebounds, five assists, two blocks and one steal, in 33 minutes. Dwight Howard only finished with five points on four shot attempts, but hauled in 11 rebounds, a steal, a block and two assists, in 27 minutes. Dennis Schroder came up big once again, with 27 points on 10-of-22 shooting and nine assists, in 31 minutes, while Taurean Prince gave the Hawks a nice boost with 16 points on 7-of-10 shooting. The Hawks shot 49 percent from the field, which is better than they did in Games 1 and 2, and also scored more points than they did in either of the first two games.

Meanwhile, the Wizards accumulated 16 assists as a team, but gave up an equalizing 16 turnovers. John Wall was just about the lone bright spot for Washington, as he led the way with 29 points and seven assists, in 32 minutes. On the other hand, Bradley Beal shot 6-of-20 from the field, including 0-of-6 from long range and finished with 12 points. The only other players to score in double digits for Washington were Brandon Jennings, with 13, and Bojan Bogdanovic, with 11. Otto Porter finished with seven points before he left the game late in the third quarter with a strained neck.

The Wizards were much better at home during the regular season but will need to find a way to win on the road in order to prevent the Hawks from tying it up at 2-2, in Game 4, which takes place in Atlanta on Monday.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the San Antonio Spurs, 110-108, in Game 4 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at FedEx Forum on Saturday. 

This was one of the tightest games of the postseason thus far, as it took an extra session to decide a winner. In fact, there were 11 ties and eight lead changes in total, with neither team leading by more than 10 points. Marc Gasol played hero, as he hit a game-winning floater with 0.7 seconds left in overtime to take a two-point lead and eventually win. Rebounding was key for Memphis, as they outrebounded San Antonio, 51-37. They also dominated the fastbreak points differential, winning that battle, 26-9. The Grizzlies ended up shooting 46 percent from the field and 44 percent from three-point range, while holding the Spurs to 42 percent from the field and 30 percent from long distance.

The Spurs (2-2) put in a valiant effort in this historic playoff game, but they fell just shy of taking a 3-1 series lead. Kawhi Leonard was incredible, as he scored a playoff career-high 43 points, to go along with eight rebounds, three assists and six steals. Tony Parker was vintage, tallying 22 points, four rebounds and five assists. LaMarcus Aldridge collected 13 points, two rebounds and two steals. Pau Gasol led the bench with eight points and 11 rebounds. 

The Grizzlies (2-2) needed this win avoid a 3-1 hole headed back to San Antonio and they showed some serious resiliency in this amazing game. Gasol not only hit the game-winner, he added 16 points, 12 rebounds and four assists to his line. Mike Conley was the Grizzlies best player, as he accumulated 35 points, nine rebounds and eight assists. Zach Randolph recorded another double-double, totaling 12 points and 11 rebounds. Vince Carter started and accrued 13 points, three rebounds and two assists. JaMychal Green was huge off the bench, as he provided 14 points and four rebounds, in addition to manning up with Kawhi Leonard. 

Game 5 will be on Tuesday back in San Antonio.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the host Portland Trail Blazers, 119-113, in Game 3 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Moda Center on Saturday. 

This was a tale of two halves, as the Warriors really took care of business in the second half. In fact, the Blazers led, 67-54, at the half, but allowed the warriors to outscore them in the second half, 65-46. A 19-1 run spanning between the third and fourth quarters was key, as that gave Golden State their largest lead up to that point and eventually won them the game. The assist-to-turnover ratio was the glaring difference, with the Warriors recording 25 assists to just seven turnovers, while the Blazers committed 16 turnovers to 17 assists. A 22-6 advantage in fastbreak points was huge for Golden State as well.

The Warriors (3-0) had to play this game without Kevin Durant, but they find themselves now in command of this series. Stephen Curry was the player of the game, as he collected 34 points, four rebounds, eight assists and two steals. Klay Thompson finished with 24 points, two rebounds and three steals. Andre Iguodala was huge off the bench, providing 16 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Draymond Green accumulated nine points, eight rebounds, seven assists, two steals and six blocks. 

The Trail Blazers (0-3) played a great first half, but were unable to sustain that for all four quarters against the best team in basketball. C.J McCollum did all he could for Portland though, as he tallied 32 points, six rebounds and two steals. Damian Lillard was just as good, amassing 31 points, seven rebounds and four assists. Evan Turner totaled 17 points, eight rebounds, three assists and two blocks. Al-Farouq Aminu and Noah Vonleh played well off the bench, combining for 24 points, 16 rebounds, five assists and two blocks.

Game 4 will be on Monday back in Portland.

The Boston Celtics defeated the host Chicago Bulls 104-87 in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs, at United Center on Friday evening. The Bulls lead the series 2-1.

The Bulls were without Rajon Rondo, who was ruled out with a fractured thumb. The Celtics took advantage by jumping on the home team early, with a 33-15 first quarter. The Bulls answered back in the second quarter with an 11-0 run, while holding the Celtics to 5-of-22 shooting the quarter. Dwyane Wade had 14 points at halftime, as the Bulls trailed 44-41. However, the second half belonged entirely to the Celtics, as they outscored the Bulls 60-46, en route to the 17-point victory. After dropping two games at home, the Celtics took a big step in the right direction with the road win.

Four of Boston's starters scored in double digits, including Jae Crowder and Isaiah Thomas, who finished with 16 points each. Al Horford was the high-point man for the Celtics with 18 points to go along with eight rebounds and six assists. Avery Bradley was solid with 15 points, seven rebounds and seven assists. 

Meanwhile, Dwyane Wade led the Bulls with 18 points on 6-of-18 shooting. Jimmy Butler followed up with 14 points and seven rebounds, while Robin Lopez finished with 12 points and six rebounds. Jerian Grant started in place of Rondo but struggled with six points, no assists and four turnovers in 15 minutes. 

Game 4 takes place in Chicago on Sunday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Houston Rockets, 115-113, in Game 3 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Friday.

Despite the fact that Oklahoma City led for all but one minute, this game was close throughout. In fact, this was a single digit margin for the entirety of the second half. All the statistics were lopsided in the Thunder's favor, as they ended up shooting 55 percent from the field and 47 percent from three-point range. Houston shot just 46 percent from the field and 29 percent from three-point range. Oklahoma City also dominated the assist-to-turnover ratio, recording 24 assists to 11 turnovers, while Houston committed 16 turnovers to just 10 assists. The Thunder also played well in transition, winning the fastbreak differential, 19-4.

The Rockets (2-1) did a great job of hanging around in a game where they didn't play well, but they fell just short of getting to a 3-0 lead. James Harden carried the load, as he accumulated 44 points, six rebounds and six assists. Lou Williams finished second on the team, dropping 22 points off the bench. Ryan Anderson was the only other starter with more than seven points, as he tallied 18 points and six rebounds. 

The Thunder (1-2) were in a must-win circumstance, as they rode some hot shooting to a huge Game 3 win. Russell Westbrook recorded his second-straight triple-double, collecting 32 points, 13 rebounds, 11 assists and three steals. Taj Gibson finished second on the team, totaling 20 points and two rebounds on 10-of-13 from the field. Andre Roberson continued his great series, accruing 12 points, six rebounds, four assists, two steals and three blocks. Victor Oladipo finished with 12 points, six rebounds, two assists and two steals.

Game 4 will be on Sunday in Oklahoma City.

The visiting Los Angeles Clippers defeated the Utah Jazz, 111-106, in Game 3 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Friday.  Los Angeles now has a 2-1 series lead.  

Despite the win, the Clippers received bad news during Friday's game.  All-Star big man Blake Griffin went down with a toe injury midway through the game. Griffin's x-rays did not show a break, but the star forward will miss at least Game 4 due to the injury.

Los Angeles (2-1) came back from down by double digits in the second half, going on an 11-0 run late in the fourth quarter to establish a lead.  The team was largely carried by superstar point guard Chris Paul, who had a team-high 34 points and 10 assists.  Paul was on fire on Friday, shooting 12-of-22 and scoring seven unanswered points with under six minutes remaining in the game.  Another crucial component for the Clippers was rebounding, as the team finished with a 41-27 advantage on the boards.  13 of those rebounds came from star big man DeAndre Jordan.

Utah (1-2) remains without star center Rudy Gobert, who went down with a knee injury on the first possession of the series.  On Friday, the Jazz enjoyed a step-up performance from All-Star forward Gordon Hayward.  Hayward had a game-high 40 points, including 25 in the first quarter.  However, Hayward also largely played Utah out of the game, committing three fourth quarter turnovers in the clutch and air-balling a late-game three-pointer.  Hayward was also responsible for throwing away the team's final inbounds pass.  

Game 4 is scheduled for Sunday in Utah.

The Cleveland Cavaliers came back from down 26 to defeat the host Indiana Pacers, 119-114, in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Thursday.  

The Cavaliers launched the largest comeback in playoff history on Thursday, coming back from down by 26 points at halftime.  Much of the comeback was due to strong play from superstar forward LeBron James.  James scored or assisted on 73 points, the most of his playoff career.  He finished the night with 41 points, 13 points, and 12 assists.  The performance moved him to seventh on the all-time playoff rebounding leader board.  

Cleveland (3-0) looks poised to move on to the semifinal round as it now holds a three-game lead over Indiana.  The Cavaliers saw three-point shooting prove key in their comeback win in Indiana on Thursday.  The team hit a whopping 21 three-pointers on the night, including six from LeBron James.  Their shooting was less stellar from the free-throw line, however, as the team went just 20-of-30 from the charity stripe.  Point guard Kyrie Irving also saw some struggles, shooting just 4-of-17 from the field for 13 points.  

Indiana (0-3) saw major output from superstar forward Paul George despite the losing effort.  George finished the night with 36 points and 15 rebounds along with nine assists.  The team also saw a stellar rebounding effort, holding a 52-40 advantage on the glass.  However, the team as a whole could not get it going from the field, shooting just 40 percent from the field.  

Game 4 will be in Indiana on Sunday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Toronto Raptors 104-77 Thursday in Game 2 of their first-round Eastern Conference playoff series at BMO Harris Bradley Center. 

It didn't take long for this game to open up, as a 15-0 run from the Bucks (2-1) to end the first quarter gave them a 20-point lead after 12 minutes, and the Raptors (1-2) managed to score just 12 points in those 12 minutes. From there, Milwaukee continued to poor it on offensively and stand tall defensively, as Toronto had just 46 points by the end of the third quarter. The Bucks shot a scorching 52.2 percent from behind the arc and 52.7 percent from the field overall. They also recorded six steals, four blocks and forced the Raptors into 15 total turnovers. It was business as usual for both Khris Middleton and Giannis Antetokounmpo, with Middleton scoring a team-high 20 points in addition to seven assists, while Antetokounmpo recorded 19 points, eight rebounds and four assists. The two wings managed to shoot a combined 15-of-25 (60 percent) from the field. 

The Raptors' stars failed to be as effective, with DeMar DeRozan putting together his worst performance of this season. DeRozan shot 0-of-8 from the field in 31 minutes Thursday night, finishing with eight points after he went 8-of-8 from the free throw line. All-star point guard Kyle Lowry wasn't much better, as he shot 4-of-10 from the field and scored just 13 points in 35 minutes -- a point total that still somehow managed to lead the team. It was a forgetful night overall for Toronto, as they shot a dreadful 33.8 percent from the field in the blowout defeat. 

All hope is not lost for the Raptors, however, as they'll still have a chance to earn home-court advantage back when the teams play Game 4 in Milwaukee on Saturday.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the San Antonio Spurs, 105-94, in Game 3 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at FedEx Forum on Thursday. 

San Antonio looked dominant in the first two games of this series, but Memphis did a nice job of bouncing back and taking care of homecourt advantage. This game was close throughout the first half, as there were nine ties and 13 lead changes in those two quarters. Memphis actually led from there on out though, outscoring San Antonio in the third quarter, 31-17. The key for the Grizzlies was their defense, as they held the Spurs to just 47 percent shooting on only 72 shots. They did that while forcing 12 turnovers from San Antonio, with Memphis commiting just five on their end. The Grizzlies ended up shooting 51 percent from the field, which was their highest mark against the Spurs all season. Much of that damage was done in the paint, with Memphis winning that battle, 44-34. San Antonio also struggled from the free-throw line, going just 16-of-28. 

The Spurs (2-1) have rode their defense all season long, but it simply wasn't there in this game. Kawhi Leonard led the way for San Antonio, as he tallied 18 points, four rebounds and three assists. LaMarcus Aldridge was second on the team, totaling 16 points and 11 rebounds. The other three starters combined for just six points, six rebounds and no assists. 

The Grizzlies (1-2) needed this win desperately after two blowout losses and they are now just one home win away from evening up this series. Zach Randolph was brilliant in his starting role, amassing 21 points and eight rebounds. Mike Conley accrued 24 points and eight assists. Marc Gasol collected 21 points, six rebounds and three assists. 

This win snapped a nine-game losing streak for the Grizzlies in the postseason. This is the first time that Memphis has cracked 100 points in 14-straight playoff games.

Game 4 will be on Saturday back in Memphis.

The Washington Wizards defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 109-101, at Verizon Center on Tuesday night in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs. The Wizards now lead the series, 2-0.

The Hawks (0-2) had a hard time scoring points against the Wizards (2-0) over their last three meetings in the regular season, and those issues re-emerged in Tuesday's Game 2. The fact that standout center Dwight Howard ran into trouble certainly didn't help their cause either, nor did the 18 turnovers they were guilty of after committing 19 in Game 1. Shooting was a problem as well, as Atlanta could only muster a 40.5 percent success rate from the field and 20.0 percent from three-point range. Meanwhile, the backcourt duo of John Wall and Bradley Beal were lethal, as they combined to score 63 points on a combined 21-of-47 from the field, including 6-of-12 from three-point range. Their contributions were key in Washington overcoming the 78-74 deficit they entered the final 12 minutes with, and in helping them put together a 35-point fourth quarter to seal the win. 

With Howard in foul trouble, Paul Millsap took on a more prominent role in the frontcourt and led the way for Atlanta with 27 points, 10 rebounds, four assists, two steals and one block. Dennis Schroder followed with 23 points, which he supplemented with six assists, four rebounds and one steal. Tim Hardaway, Jr. followed with 19 points, two assists and one rebound. Taurean Prince provided 12 points, four boards and one assist. Howard could only muster six points, seven rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block over 20 minutes. Kent Bazemore paced the second unit with eight points, five rebounds and two blocks.

Wall led the way for the Wizards with 32 points, nine assists, five rebounds, one steal and one block. Beal was right behind his backcourt mate with 31 points, which he complemented with three assists, two rebounds and three steals. Marcin Gortat posted a 14-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three assists, five blocks and one steal. Much like Howard, Markieff Morris also ran into issues with the ref's whistle, totaling just three points, three rebounds, two assists and two blocks over 20 minutes. Brandon Jennings led the bench with 10 points, four rebounds and two assists. 

The two teams will reconvene on Saturday at Philips Arena for Game 3.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Oklahoma City Thunder, 115-111, in Game 2 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Toyota Center on Wednesday. 

Despite Oklahoma City leading for the majority of this game, Houston made the final run that ultimately proved to be decisive. In fact, the Thunder led 86-74 in the third quarter and allowed the Rockets to go off from there. In addition, Houston grabbed their first lead with only seven minutes left, as they won the fourth quarter, 29-22, en route to a comeback win. The Thunder actually turned a 12-point lead into a 10-point deficit in just 12 minutes of action between the third and fourth quarters. Oklahoma City dominated the stat sheet, as they won the rebounding, steals, blocks, fastbreak points and turnover differentials. Shooting was key for Houston, as they hit 49 percent of their shots, while holding the Thunder to just 41 percent from the field on their end. The Rockets also dominated in bench production, outscoring Oklahoma City's bench, 50-24.

The Thunder (0-2) dominated for most of this game, but they'll be going back home in a huge hole after a collapse in the fourth quarter. Russell Westbrook did all he could though, as he collected 51 points, 10 rebounds, 13 assists and four steals. He did however go 4-of-18 from the field in the fourth quarter and finished the game shooting just 17-of-43. Andre Roberson finished second on the team, accruing 12 points, eight rebounds, two steals and three blocks. Victor Oladipo totaled 11 points, nine rebounds and three assists.

The Rockets (2-0) were far from their best in this game, but they'll be leaving home with a dominant 2-0 advantage in this series. James Harden was once again the star, as he accumulated 35 points, four rebounds and eight assists. Patrick Beverley was the only other starter in double figures, as he tallied 15 points, six rebounds and four assists. Eric Gordon was huge off the bench, providing 22 points, four rebounds and two assists. Lou Williams dropped 21 points of his own off the bench in just 21 minutes of action.

Game 3 will be in Oklahoma City on Friday.

The host Golden State Warriors defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 110-81, in Game 2 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Oracle Arena on Wednesday.  

Prior to the game, it was announced that Golden State star Kevin Durant would sit the game out due to a strained calf.  Warriors coach Steve Kerr defended the decision, saying he would "feel like an idiot" if Durant were to re-aggravate the injury.  Durant is officially listed as day-to-day and may rest again in Game 3 given the Warriors' comfortable cushion.  

Golden State (2-0) showed off its top-3 ranked defense throughout the game, holding Portland to just 33 percent shooting on the night.  With Durant sitting out and star players Steph Curry and Klay Thompson combining for just 35 points on 12-of-35 shooting, it was defense that proved key to earning the blowout win.  The team finished with eight steals and a whopping 11 blocks.  Four of those blocks came from bench big man JaVale McGee, who was superb in limited playing time.  McGee shot a perfect 7-of-7 from the field for 15 points.  

Portland (0-2) will head back to its home court in a fairly deep hole after dropping each of the first two games of the series by double figures.  After what was a miraculous first half for the Blazers' backcourt in Game 1, Damian Lillard and C.J. McCollum went ice cold in Game 2, combining to shoot 9-of-34 for just 23 points. The team as a whole saw horrendous shooting splits, hitting just 33 percent of its shots from the field and 20 percent from beyond the arc.  

Game 3 will take place in Portland on Saturday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Milwaukee Bucks, 106-100, at Air Canada Centre on Tuesday in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs. The series is now tied 1-1. 

The Raptors (1-1) came in with the sense of urgency that's unique to being in danger of going down 2-0 in a playoff series on one's home court. The Bucks (1-1) demonstrated once again that they are legitimate postseason players, seemingly staying with a more experienced Toronto squad shot for shot throughout all four quarters. However, it was the Raptors' experience and defense that appeared to give them an edge in the end. Kyle Lowry stayed on Giannis Antetokounmpo's hip on a late possession, forcing a pass despite the latter's considerable size advantage. The Raptors' point guard then coolly drained a 20-foot jumper over the tight coverage of Malcolm Brogdon to give the hosts some all-important breathing room at 104-100 with 8.9 seconds remaining. A missed Brogdon three-pointer and two Patrick Patterson free throws later, Toronto had effectively evened the first-round series at 1-1. 

Antetokounmpo paced Milwaukee with a 24-point, 15-rebound double-double that also included seven assists and two steals. Khris Middleton was next with 20 points, which he supplemented with five boards, two assists and one steal. Greg Monroe followed with a bench-leading 18 points, which he supplemented with four boards, one assist and one steal. Tony Snell poured in 14 points and added two rebounds. Brogdon mustered a modest seven points, four rebounds, three assists and one block. 

DeMar DeRozan led the way for Toronto with 23 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Lowry followed with 22 points, five assists, four rebounds, three steals and one block. Serge Ibaka provided 16 points, seven rebounds, six assists and a pair of blocks. Cory Joseph led the second unit with 11 points and added one assist. Jonas Valanciunas compiled a 10-point, 10-rebound double-double. DeMarre Carroll rounded out the starting five's productive night with nine points, one rebound, one assist and one block.

The two teams now head to BMO Harris Bradley Center in Milwaukee, where Game 3 will unfold on Thursday night.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the host Boston Celtics, 111-97, in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs at TD Garden on Tuesday. 

A 2-0 start by the Celtics wouldn't have surprised anyone in this series, but the Bulls are the ones who holds that honor now. Chicago put in a dominant performance, as they led for over 40 minutes of this game and won each individual quarter by at least three points. Defense was key for the Bulls, as they recorded 12 steals and forced 16 turnovers from the Celtics. Shooting was also key, with Chicago shooting 51 percent from the field, 40 percent from three-point range and 79 percent from the free-throw line. Boston shot just 46 percent from the field, 30 percent from three-point range and 58 percent from the free-throw line.

The Bulls (2-0) now go back home with a two-game advantage, as they are on the verge of history as an eight-seed. Jimmy Butler was the player of the game, as he collected 22 points, eight rebounds, eight assists, four steals and two blocks. Dwyane Wade matched those 22 points, adding four rebounds and two assists to his tally. Rajon Rondo flirted with a triple-double, accumulating 11 points, nine rebounds, 14 assists and five steals Robin Lopez totaled 18 points, eight rebounds and two steals. Paul Zipser led the bench with 16 points.

The Celtics (0-2) are leaving home winless and they have dug themselves quite the hole headed back to Chicago. Isaiah Thomas once again led the way, as he accrued 20 points, four rebounds and two assists. Jae Crowder finished with 16 points, three rebounds and four assists. Marcus Smart played well off the bench, providing 13 points, eight rebounds, two assists, two steals and two blocks. 

Game 3 will be in Chicago on Friday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the Utah Jazz 99-91 in Game 2 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs Tuesday at Staples Center.

The Clippers (1-1) wasted no time opening up Tuesday's contest, holding a lead as large as 12 in the first quarter and ultimately ending the period with an 11-point advantage. From there, while the Jazz (1-1) managed to come close on multiple occasions throughout the next 36 minutes, they were never able to take the lead or even tie the game, as Los Angeles held from the lead from the very start at 2-0 to the very end. Chris Paul was sensational for the Clippers, making big shot after big shot down the stretch and finishing with 21 points on 9-of-15 shooting from the field and 10 assists in 33 minutes. Blake Griffin led the way scoring for Los Angeles with a game-high 24 points, while DeAndre Jordan was a monster on the glass, scoring 18 points on 9-of-11 shooting and grabbing 15 rebounds. As a team, the Clippers ended up shooting an impressive 52.4 percent from the field en route to tying the series.

For Utah, some timely three-pointers allowed them to hang around, with the team shooting 10-of-25 (40 percent) from the field overall, but they just didn't have enough offensively Tuesday night to comeback from an early deficit. Gordon Hayward scored a team-high 20 points, but he shot just 5-of-15 from the field. Game 1's hero Joe Johnson came off the bench to hit just six of his 15 shots en route to 13 points in 29 minutes, while George Hill added just 12 points of his own on a rough 5-of-12 shooting performance. In the end, the absence of Rudy Gobert (knee) on defense really hurt the Jazz in this contest, as the lack of size led to plenty of uncontested shots for the Clippers in the lane. 

The teams will play Game 3 on Friday in Salt Lake City.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the Indiana Pacers, 117-111, in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs at Quicken Loans Arena on Monday. 

Cleveland haven't been dominant in either of the first two games, but they took care of business to go up 2-0 in this opening round. Despite this final scoreline being close, the Cavaliers were in control for the majority of the game. In fact, Cleveland led for the final three quarters, with the game never getting within four points after the first quarter. The third quarter is where they separated themselves, outscoring the Pacers, 33-20. Cleveland's offense was extremely efficient, shooting 55 percent from the field, 42 percent from three-point range and 87 percent from the free-throw line. 

The Pacers (0-2) have put in valiant efforts in both of these opening road games, but they're leaving Cleveland in a big hole. Paul George once again carried Indiana, as he collected 32 points, eight rebounds and seven assists. Jeff Teague finished second on the team, accruing 23 points, four rebounds and four assists. Thaddeus Young totaled 16 points, three rebounds and six steals. Lance Stephenson was the only other Pacer in double figures, providing 13 points, two rebounds, four assists and two steals off the bench. 

The Cavaliers (2-0) now have a strangle hold on this series, as they took care of homecourt advantage. LeBron James was the player of the game, as he accumulated 25 points, 10 rebounds, seven assists, four steals and four blocks. Kyrie Irving led the team in scoring, amassing 37 points, two rebounds and two assists. Kevin Love put up 27 points, 11 rebounds and three assists on an efficient 6-of-7 from the field. J.R. Smith had a recurrence of his hamstring injury and was unable to return in the second half. 

Game 3 will be on Thursday in Indiana.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 96-82, in Game 2 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs on Monday at AT&T Center. 

San Antonio took an early lead in the game but had to stave off a late comeback effort from Memphis.  Still, the number one-ranked defense of the Spurs factored in, as the team played stiflingly tight D on the Grizz to earn the win.  Memphis was held to just 37 percent shooting on the night and made only seven three-pointers, with shooting proving to be an obstacle in their comeback effort. 

The Spurs (2-0) were led by outstanding play from superstar forward Kawhi Leonard.  The former Finals MVP had a playoff career-high of 37 points on staggering 9-of-14 shooting from the field and 19-of-19 from the free-throw line.  He added a team-high 11 rebounds.  The win was hardly a one-man show, though, as San Antonio shot over 45 percent from the field and went a whopping 31-of-32 at the free-throw line as a team.  Guard Danny Green added a significant franchise milestone to his resume, as he passed Bruce Bowen for second in Spurs playoff three-pointers made with the 162nd made three-pointer of his playoff career.

Memphis (0-2) was put in a tough spot, falling behind by over 20 points in the second quarter.  Veteran point guard Mike Conley was one of the lone bright spots for the Grizzlies in the game, as he led the team with 24 points and eight assists with just one turnover.  Still, finding offense proved a struggle for the "grit and grind" Grizzlies.  The team went to the line only 15 times and hit just 37 percent of its shots from the field.  The team has now dropped its first two playoff games by a margin of 42 points.  

Memphis will host Game 3 on Thursday.

The Washington Wizards defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 114-107, in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference playoffs first-round at Verizon Center on Sunday. 

Despite the fact there were only two ties and two lead changes in total, this game was close throughout. In fact, it was a single-digit margin for nearly 40 minutes, with neither team leading by more than 15 points. It took a comeback for Washington to pull out Game 1, as they rode a 38-28 third quarter to overcome a halftime deficit. The assist-to-turnover ratio was the decisive statistic, with the Wizards recording 28 assists to 12 turnovers, while the Hawks committed 21 turnovers to just 18 assists.

The Hawks were one of the hottest teams in the league headed into the playoffs, but playing in Washington is a different animal. Dennis Schroder led the way for Atlanta, as he tallied 25 points, three rebounds and nine assists. Paul Millsap finished with 19 points and two rebounds. Dwight Howard scored just seven points, but brought down a game-high 14 rebounds. Kent Bazemore led the bench, providing 12 points, three rebounds and three assists. 

The Wizards struggled near the end of the season, but they're clearly comfortable with playing at home. John Wall was the player of the game, as he collected 32 points, four rebounds and 14 assists. Bradley Beal amassed 22 points, three rebounds, three assists and three steals. Markieff Morris accumulated 21 points, seven rebounds, two assists and four blocks. Marcin Gortat recorded a double-double, totaling 14 points and 10 rebounds.

Game 2 will be back in Washington on Wednesday.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 121-109, in Game 1 of the Western Conference first-round playoff series at Oracle Arena on Sunday afternoon. Golden State has a 1-0 lead in the best-of-seven series.

The Warriors (1-0) came into the series knowing they'd finally have their Big Three of Stephen Curry, Kevin Durant and Klay Thompson on the floor together and at full strength to open the defense of their Western Conference championship. However, the sometimes forgotten man on the Golden State offense, the jack-of-all-trades Draymond Green, stepped up his offensive game considerably in the opening tilt of the first-round series. Green provided a near triple-double of 19 points, 12 rebounds and nine assists, while adding five blocks and three steals in a superb all-around effort. Both of the latter contributions were game-high figures, and his defense helped spearhead a pivotal 15-2 run in the fourth quarter for the Warriors that subdued what had been a feisty Blazers (0-1) squad. Golden State finished with a 53.1 percent success rate from the floor and limited Portland to a 43 percent tally.

The Blazers were led by C.J. McCollum, who poured in 41 points and added eight rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. He took a whopping 28 shots on the afternoon, impressively draining 16. Backcourt mate Damian Lillard followed with 34 points, which he supplemented with five rebounds, three assists, two steals and one block. Evan Turner drew the start and posted a 12-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included four assists and one steal. Moe Harkless managed 11 points, three boards, one assist, two steals and one block. Noah Vonleh couldn't contribute much on the offensive end, mustering just two points. He did haul in five rebounds and dished out four assists.

Durant paced the Warriors with 32 points, which he complemented with 10 rebounds, two assists and one block. Curry poured in 29 points and added five rebounds, four assists, one steal and one block. Thompson posted 15 points, three rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. Ian Clark led the second unit with 12 points, two boards and one steal.

The two teams will reconvene at Oracle Arena for Game 2 on Wednesday night.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the host Boston Celtics, 106-102, in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs at TD Garden on Sunday. 

Boston had one of the worst records ever for a number-one seed and games like this show that they have a tough road ahead of them. Rebounding was the glaring difference in the game, with Chicago winning that battle, 53-36. They also got some great bench production, outscoring the Boston bench, 35-22. Free-throw shooting was also key, with the Bulls hitting 20-of-23 from the charity stripe, while the Celtics went just 14-of-19. It was a close game throughout, as there were 14 ties and 10 lead changes in total, with neither team leading by double-digits at any point.

The Bulls snuck into the playoffs thanks to their great rebounding and that was the key in this victory. Jimmy Butler was the player of the game, as he collected 30 points, nine rebounds and three assists. Bobby Portis was huge off the bench, providing 19 points, nine rebounds, three assists and two steals on 8-of-10 shooting. Robin Lopez recorded a double-double, totaling 14 points and 11 rebounds. Rajon Rondo accrued 12 points, seven rebounds and six assists. Dwyane Wade contributed 11 points, five rebounds, six assists, two steals and two blocks.

The Celtics have been dominated on the boards all season long and it was once again their downfall in this defeat. Isaiah Thomas carried Boston, as he tallied 33 points, five rebounds and six assists. Al Horford accumulated 19 points, seven rebounds and eight assists. Avery Bradley was the only other Celtic in double figures, as he amassed 14 points, three rebounds, two assists and three steals. 

Game 2 will be back in Boston on Tuesday.

The host Houston Rockets defeated the visiting Oklahoma City Thunder, 118-87, in Game 1 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Toyota Center on Sunday. 

The series was hotly anticipated due to the marquee matchup between two of the leading contenders for the MVP award, Houston's James Harden and OKC's Russell Westbrook.  Harden was able to lead the league in assists throughout the regular season while taking the unexpectedly hot Rockets to third in the Western Conference.  Westbrook, meanwhile, broke the historic record of 41 triple-doubles set by Oscar Robertson over 50 years prior.  He did so while also earning the title of league scoring champion.  

On Sunday, the two squared off in their first postseason matchup, and the battle was fairly lopsided.  Though Westbrook posted strong individual numbers, including 22 points and 11 rebounds, Harden and the Rockets rolled by OKC as Harden scored a ridiculous 37 points.  Harden also outperformed Westbrook in terms of managing the ball, turning it over just twice while Westbrook coughed the ball up nine times in total.

For Houston as a whole, the series got off to an ideal start.  The team shot almost 50 percent and shut the Thunder down on the defensive end en route to a 31-point victory.  Houston's starting backcourt combined for 58 points and seven three-pointers.  They also saw an impressive performance from their bench, as the bench combined for 38 points, including 15 from veteran big man Nene Hilario.  

OKC, meanwhile, saw a miserable start to their playoff campaign.  The team struggled to contain superstar James Harden, often being forced into undesirable defensive matchups with the potential MVP.  In particular, big man Enes Kanter appeared to struggle with the matchup, which he ended up forced into numerous times.  Struggles were compounded by shooting woes, as the team hit only 37 percent of its attempts from the field.  

Game 2 will be in Houston on Wednesday.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the visiting Indiana Pacers, 109-108, in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs Saturday at Quicken Loans Arena.

Two teams that know each other's strengths and weaknesses put on a show to open the postseason, with superstars LeBron James and Paul George matching each other virtually shot-for-shot in a tightly-contested showdown. The Pacers put a scare into the Cavs as time wound down after entering the fourth quarter trailing 94-84. Indiana outscored Cleveland 24-17 over the final 12 minutes and after a George three-pointer with 40 seconds remaining, had a chance to steal what would have been a huge series-opening victory. However, C.J. Miles' 14-foot jumper with less than a second on the clock couldn't find the net, allowing the defending champions to escape with the win.

George led the way for the Pacers with 29 points, seven assists, five rebounds and one steal. Lance Stephenson, a late-season addition that's paid some dividends, followed with 16 points, seven boards and three assists. Jeff Teague pitched in with 15 points, four assists and two rebounds. Myles Turner and Monta Ellis turned in matching 11-point efforts, with the former adding eight rebounds, one assists, four steals and one block, and the latter supplying four boards, one assist and one steal. Thaddeus Young mustered a modest eight points but posted nine rebounds and four assists.

James paced the Cavs with 32 points, 13 assists, six rebounds and three steals. Kyrie Irving registered 23 points, six assists, three rebounds, two steals and one block. Kevin Love managed 17 points, four rebounds, one assist and two blocks. Channing Frye produced a bench-leading 11 points, which he supplemented with two rebounds and two assists. Tristan Thompson pitched in with eight points, 13 rebounds and one assist.

The two teams reconvene on Monday night in Cleveland for Game 2.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host Toronto Raptors, 97-83, in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference first-round playoffs at Air Canada Center on Saturday evening. 

The Bucks wasted no time, as they came out strong with a 30-22 first quarter. The Raptors answered by outscoring the Bucks 29-16 in the second quarter, to take a 51-46 lead into halftime. The second half started out the same way the first half did, with a strong third quarter from the Bucks, however the Raptors were not able to produce the counter punch, and were outscored 51-32 over the third and fourth quarters. The young Bucks team stole Game 1 from the third-place Raptors, instantly putting a big question mark on the series. It is not panic time yet though for Toronto, as the Raptors have now dropped Game 1 in the first round of the playoffs nine times in a row, dating back to 2002. 

Giannis Antetokounmpo led the way for Milwaukee with 28 points, eight rebounds, three assists, two steals and one block, in 38 minutes. The rookie, Malcolm Brogdon came up huge for the Bucks with 16 points, six rebounds and two assists, in 34 minutes. Greg Monroe provided a big boost off the bench, with 14 points and a huge 15 rebounds, in 26 minutes. 

Meanwhile, the Raptors were slowed by the Bucks' solid defense, shooting only 36.0 percent from the field, including 21.7 percent from long range. DeMar DeRozan led the way with 27 points on 7-of-21 shooting, and eight rebounds, in 39 minutes, while Serge Ibaka followed up with 19 points, 15 rebounds and three blocks, in 36 minutes. Kyle Lowry struggled, shooting only 2-of-11 from the field, including 0-of-6 from downtown, on his way to four points, six assists and two rebounds, in 34 minutes.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 111-82, in Game 1 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at AT&T Center on Saturday.

San Antonio were heavy favorites in this series and they left very little doubt with this dominating victory. This game was actually close throughout the first half, with San Antonio taking control in the second half. In fact, the Spurs outscored the Grizzlies in the second half, 62-33. Defense was key for San Antonio, as they held Memphis to 39 percent from the field and 35 percent from long distance. The Spurs ended up shooting 53 percent from the field, as well as from three-point range. Rebounding was key as well, with San Antonio winning that battle, 43-35.

The Grizzlies fought hard in the first half, but got obliterated in the second half. Marc Gasol carried Memphis, as he tallied 32 points, five rebounds, two assists and two blocks. Mike Conley was the only other starter with more than five points, as he collected 13 points, five rebounds, seven assists and three steals. Zach Randolph really struggled off the bench, as he totaled just six points and three rebounds on 3-of-13 shooting. 

The Spurs have been riding their defense all season and stifling performances like this show why. Kawhi Leonard was the player of the game, as he accumulated 32 points, three rebounds, five assists and two steals on 11-of-14 shooting. LaMarcus Aldridge finished second on the team, amassing 20 points, six rebounds and two assists, Tony Parker finished with 18 points, two rebounds and two assists. 

Game 2 will be on Monday back in San Antonio.

The Utah Jazz defeated the host Los Angeles Clippers, 97-95, in Game 1 of the Western Conference first-round playoffs at Staples Center on Saturday. 

These two teams finished with even 51-31 records and if this games any indication, this will be one of the tightest series of the playoffs. In fact, there were six ties and 11 lead changes in total, with neither team leading by more than eight points. Joe Johnson was the hero, as he hit the game-winning floater at the buzzer to pull out the win. What really carried the Jazz was their three-point shooting, as they hit 8-of-19 from long range, while Los Angeles went just 8-of-24. Bench production was a huge factor as well, with the Jazz' bench outscoring the Clippers bench, 47-15.

The Jazz lost Rudy Gobert due to a knee sprain in the opening minute, but escaped with an impressive road win. Johnson was the player of the game, as he provided 21 points, three rebounds, three assists and three steals off the bench, in addition to the game-winner. Gordon Hayward totaled 19 points, 10 rebounds and three assists. George Hill started at point guard and collected 16 points, four rebounds and two assists. Derrick Favors was also a nice spark off the bench, accruing 15 points, six rebounds and two assists. 

The Clippers had been dominant against the Jazz over recent seasons, but this close-fought battle indicate a new era. Chris Paul was the Clippers best player, as he accumulated 25 points, seven rebounds, 11 assists and three steals. Blake Griffin led the team in scoring, amassing 26 points, seven rebounds and three assists. DeAndre Jordan recorded a double-double, contributing 10 points, 15 rebounds and three blocks. 

Game 2 is back in Los Angeles on Tuesday.

The Orlando Magic defeated the Detroit Pistons, 113-109, at Amway Center on Wednesday evening.

The Magic (29-53) checked into the regular-season finale looking to finish the season on an up note after losing seven of their previous eight games. They got off to a magnificent start in that regard with a 38-point first quarter, but the Pistons (37-45) clawed their way back throughout the game. Ultimately, it was stellar shooting (48.3 percent from field, 52.0 percent from three-point range) for Orlando and a trio of triple-doubles from Aaron Gordon, Nikola Vucevic and Elfrid Payton that spearheaded the much-needed win.

Ish Smith and Kentavious Caldwell-Pope led the way for the visitors with matching 20-point efforts, with the former adding 10 assists and four rebounds and the latter supplying four rebounds and one steal. Reggie Bullock followed with a bench-leading 17 points, three assists, two rebounds and two steals. Boban Marjanovic contributed a 14-point, 11-rebound double-double in 21 minutes that also included three blocks and one steal. Henry Ellenson tallied 12 points, six rebounds, one assist and one steal in 19 minutes. Andre Drummond managed nine points but also hauled in 14 rebounds and dished out two assists. 

Aaron Gordon paced Orlando with a 32-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included two blocks and one steal. Elfrid Payton registered a 21-point, 13-assist double-double along with five boards. Nikola Vucevic provided an 18-point, 11-rebound double-double that also featured an assist, two steals and two blocks. Evan Fournier contributed 12 points, three rebounds and two assists. Jodie Meeks led the bench with 12 points and one assist.

With Wednesday's win, the Magic secured a 3-1 season victory in the series.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 98-83, at Quicken Loans Arena on Wednesday night.

The Raptors (51-31) gave the likely exhausted DeMar DeRozan the night off for the season finale with playoff seeding secured. As has been the case in past games when DeRozan has sat, Norman Powell stepped into the starting five and excelled against a Cavaliers (51-31) team sitting LeBron James, Kevin Love and Kyrie Irving despite the top seed in the Eastern Conference being within reach. Powell tallied a game-high 25 points, which he supplemented with two rebounds, two assists and one steal. Kyle Lowry posted 13 points, four assists, two rebounds and one steal. Jonas Valanciunas matched Lowry's scoring total and added seven rebounds, one assist and one steal. Bruno Caboclo led the bench with 11 points, four rebounds, one assist and one block.

The Cavs were led by a modest 11-point effort from Iman Shumpert that was complemented by three rebounds, three assists and two steals. Deron Williams followed with 10 points, four assists and three rebounds. Tristan Thompson matched Williams' scoring total and added four rebounds and one steal. Derrick Williams led the bench with 10 points as well, and added four rebounds and three assists. Dahntay Jones and James Jones contributed matching nine-point efforts as reserves as well, with the former providing two rebounds and one assist and the latter compiling six boards, two assists and one block.

Despite the Toronto win Wednesday, the Cavs easily triumphed in the season series by a 3-1 margin. Cleveland will enter the playoffs as the No. 2 seed in the Eastern Conference, while Toronto will be slotted third.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Milwaukee Bucks, 112-94, at TD Garden on Wednesday night.

The mission Wednesday night for the Celtics (53-29) couldn't have been any clearer: win and there was a high probability that the East's top seed was theirs, considering the Cleveland Cavaliers were resting their Big Three against the Toronto Raptors. That made Boston's first-quarter performance all the more maddening, as they fell behind 36-25 in the first 12 minutes despite the Bucks (42-40) resting Giannis Antetokounmpo and Khris Middleton, among others. The Celtics righted the ship after that point, however, taking a 57-56 lead into halftime. After a tightly-contested third quarter, Boston pulled away in the fourth by doubling up their visitors, 32-16. They featured a balanced attack that overcame a poor shooting night from Isaiah Thomas, as six players managed double-digit scoring.

Michael Beasley and Spencer Hawes co-led the Bucks with 15-point efforts from the starting five and bench, respectively. Beasley added five rebounds, two assists, three steals and two blocks, while Hawes contributed five rebounds and two assists. Rashad Vaughn pitched in with 14 points, four assists, three rebounds, two steals and one block. Malcolm Brogdon posted 11 points, five boards, three assists, one steal and one block. Greg Monroe was productive as a reserve as well with 10 points, six rebounds and four assists, while Thon Maker totaled nine points, six boards, three assists and three blocks. 

Gerald Green actually paced the Celtics with 18 points, six rebounds and one assist in 21 minutes off the bench. Amir Johnson and Jae Crowder supplied matching 16-point efforts, with the former adding five rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block, and the latter registering five boards, two assists and three steals. Thomas managed 13 points, eight assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block but only shot 3-for-11 from the field. Al Horford collected 12 points, six rebounds, two assists and two steals. Jaylen Brown amassed 10 points, four rebounds, one assist and one steal in 22 minutes off the bench. 

With Wednesday's win, the Celtics claimed the season series, 2-1. Boston will enter the postseason as the top dog in the East, while the Bucks will be the No. 6 seed.

The New York Knicks defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 114-113, at Madison Square Garden on Wednesday night.

The Knicks (31-51) got a surprise entrant into their starting five when Carmelo Anthony, who had missed the previous two games with a sore knee, decided to play in what could be his final game in a New York uniform. The All-Star excelled during his time on the court, posting a first unit-leading 17 points, which he supplemented with two rebounds, one assist and one steal over just 23 minutes. The game between the two long-eliminated teams was competitive throughout, and fittingly, came down to the final seconds. Maurice Ndour, who has provided some encouraging performances in the last several games, made a two-point shot with 18 seconds remaining to give the Knicks the 114-113 lead. The Sixers (28-54) then saw Nik Stauskas twice try to help them take the lead, both times to no avail; his layup with seven seconds remaining was blocked by Marshall Plumlee, and his 25-foot three-point jumper at the buzzer misfired as well, sealing the win for the home squad. Both teams shot very well, with Philadephia managing a 50.5 percent success rate and New York draining 51.3 percent of their attempts. The Knicks were the sloppier squad, however, turning the ball over 20 times on the night.

Justin Anderson led the visitors with 26 points and added three assists, two rebounds, three steals and one block. He impressively missed just one of the 10 shots he took. Alex Poythress provided 18 points, six rebounds, one assist and one steal. Richaun Holmes totaled 15 points, seven boards and one steal. Timothe Luwawu-Cabarrot posted 14 points, three assists and two rebounds. Tiago Splitter and Stauskas led the bench with matching 12-point efforts.

Justin Holiday actually led the Knicks off the bench with 20 points, five rebounds, one assist, two steals and one block. Plumlee pitched in with a 14-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included the aforementioned block of Stauskas. Chasson Randle managed 12 points, three rebounds and two steals off the bench. Mindaugas Kuzminskas became the fourth member of the second unit with double-digit scoring by pouring in 11 points, which he complemented with four rebounds. No other member of the starting five besides Anthony posted double-digit scoring, but Ron Baker and Courtney Lee had eight points apiece, while Willy Hernangomez mustered seven points but also hauled in 10 boards and dished out three assists in only 18 minutes.

With Wednesday's win, the Knicks ensured a 2-2 split of the season series, with both of their wins having come by one point each.

The Miami Heat defeated the Washington Wizards, 110-102, at American Airlines Arena on Wednesday.

Miami needed a win here and some help to reach the postseason and they did their portion, but still missed out due to a Chicago win. The middle quarters were key for Miami, as they outscored Washington, 68-50. Rebounding is what carried the Heat to a victory, as they outrebounded the Wizards, 51-34. It wasn't just the rebounding, as they also outscored Washington in the paint, 60-46.

The Wizards (49-33) were locked into the four-seed in the east prior to this game, so this loss is far from an issue for this title contender. Trey Burke led the way for Washington, as he provided 27 points on 10-of-13 shooting off the bench. Marcin Gortat led the starters, as he totaled 16 points and five rebounds. Sheldon McClellan played well off the bench too, dropping 18 points in a career-high 34 minutes. 

The Heat (41-41) did an amazing job of getting back to .500, but they fell just short of a playoff berth. In fact, they finished the season on a 30-11 run to tie for the eight-seed in the east, but they fell shy due to a tiebreaker to the Chicago Bulls. Goran Dragic led the way for Miami, as he accrued 28 points, four rebounds and five assists. Hassan Whiteside amassed 24 points and 18 rebounds. James Johnson flirted with a triple-double, collecting 12 points, eight rebounds and eight assists.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 112-73, at United Center on Wednesday. 

This game meant much more to Chicago than Brooklyn and a 39-point margin shows just that. It was a wire-to-wire win for the Bulls, as they led by 14 after the first quarter and ended up winning the fourth quarter, 37-17, to pull away in dominating fashion. Three-point shooting was a glaring difference, with Brooklyn hitting just 3-of-33 and Chicago going 14-of-30. Rebounding was a huge factor as well, with Chicago winning that battle, 62-48. It was the Bulls defense that was especially feisty, as they held Brooklyn to 33 percent shooting and that aforementioned ugly three-point total.

The Nets (20-62) played this game without most of their starters and that was evident by this final scoreline. Archie Goodwin was Brooklyn's best player, as he provided 20 points, seven rebounds and four assists. K.J. McDaniels finished second on the team, dropping 15 points and six rebounds off the bench as well. Caris LeVert was the only starter in double figures, as he totaled 10 points, five rebounds and two assists. 

The Bulls (41-41) needed this win to clinch a playoff berth and they did it in dominating fashion. Jimmy Butler was the player of the game, as he tallied 25 points, six rebounds, four assists, four steals and two blocks. Paul Zipser finished second on the team, amassing 21 points and six rebounds off the bench. Bobby Portis recorded a double-double off the bench as well, accruing 12 points and 10 rebounds.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 100-93, at FedEx Forum on Wednesday.

This game meant very little for both of these teams, but it was still a close game. In fact, this matchup was a single-digit margin for over 45 minutes. The key for Dallas was defense, as they held Memphis to 39 percent from the field and 32 percent from three-point range. It took a late run by the Mavericks to comeback, as they outscored the Grizzlies, 30-19, in the fourth quarter. 

The Mavericks (33-49) had nothing to play for here, but they ended the season on a good note with this upset win. Nicolas Brussino led the way, as he tallied 15 points, seven rebounds, two assists and two steals in a rare start, Devin Harris matched those 15 points, adding eight assists off the bench. Dwight Powell went just 2-of-11 from the field, but still finished with 11 points and three rebounds.

The Grizzlies (43-39) didn't have anything to play for here and it was evident by this bad loss. Mike Conley led the team in scoring despite playing just 17 minutes, as he collected 15 points, two rebounds and two assists. Zach Randolph led the bench, as he totaled 15 points, five rebounds and two assists, Marc Gasol amassed 13 points, eight rebounds and four assists.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves 123-118 Wednesday at Toyota Center. 

The final score of Wednesday's contest suggests the game was a lot closer than it actually was, as while the team entered halftime tied up at 60 points each, the Rockets (55-27) elected to run away with the game in the third period, outscoring the Timberwolves (31-51) by 14 points and holding a lead as large as 17. Minnesota attempted to inch their way back into the game over the course of the final 12 minutes, but they eventually just ran out of time. James Harden led the way with yet another triple-double to end the season, as he finished with a team-high 27 points, 12 assists and 10 rebounds in 35 minutes. Clint Capela added a double-double with 22 points and 10 rebounds, while Ryan Andersen added 20 points of his own on a night where the Houston starters weren't expected to play a full load. In the end, they ended up accounting for 94 of the team's 123 points. 

As for the Timberwolves, with Wednesday's loss, they end their year on a six-game losing streak and are now tied for the sixth-worst record in the NBA. Karl-Anthony Towns capped off a terrific individual season with yet another terrific individual performance, finishing with a game-high 28 points and 21 rebounds. Andrew Wiggins added 21 points of his own, while Shabazz Muhammed contributed in a big way off the bench, finishing with 22 points in just 22 minutes as a reserve. As a team, it was a superb shooting performance from Minnesota, as they hit 52.7 percent of their field goal attempts. They just gave a lackluster defensive effort in their final outing of the 2016-17 season.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the Oklahoma City Thunder 111-105 Wednesday at Chesapeake Energy Arena.

Wednesday's battle ended up being a battle between a team that only played seven players and a team that was contempt with where they were before the start of the postseason. The Nuggets (40-42) were the former, and the difference in the matchup ended up simply being that Denver had Nikola Jokic and their counterparts didn't. Jokic topped off a breakout season with another tremendous all-around game, posting 29 points, 16 rebounds and eight assists in 40 minutes. The Nuggets' other young star, Jamal Murray, also had a great game to close out a strong rookie campaign, scoring 27 points of his own in 41 minutes. In the end, it was Denver's ability to get fouled and to the free throw line that ultimately led them to victory, as they got to the line 32 times and hit 26 of those attempts. 

As for the Thunder (47-35), while four of their five regular starters were active, none of them ended up playing a full load of minutes. Most notably, Russell Westbrook played just 18 minutes, and in that time, he shot 2-of-10 from the field en route to scoring five points, but he did manage to dish out eight assists and grab five rebounds. Five Oklahoma City players scored in double figures, but the highest total ended up being just 13 points from both Taj Gibson and Jerami Grant. It wasn't a game the Thunder were particularity interested in winning or losing, hence why all 13 active players saw the floor for at least 10 minutes despite the game being close down the stretch. The Thunder will now move onto their first-round playoff matchup against the No. 3 seeded Rockets.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Atlanta Hawks 106-84 Wednesday at Bankers Life Fieldhouse. 

The Pacers (42-40) came into Wednesday's game with their playoff hopes cleanly laid out for them: they win and they're in. Fortunately for them, they were going against a Hawks (43-39) team that rested all of their key players after clinching the No. 5 seed with a win on Monday. The result was a beat down from Indiana, as they essentially led the game wire-to-wire on the back of their star, Paul George. George finished with a game-high 32 points and 11 rebounds in 40 minutes, as the potential All-NBA performer left it all on the floor when his team needed him to the most. Jeff Teague added 19 points and seven assists but left late in the game after coming down awkwardly on his ankle. His status will likely be updated over the course of the next couple of days. 

As for the Hawks, they had nothing to play for and will be well-rested before their first-round series against the Wizards starts. In the starter's absence, Ersan Ilyasova led the way with 15 points in just 18 minutes, as he was essentially rested prior to the postseason as well. Overall, it was an ugly game for the depleted Atlanta squad, as the 86 points was their lowest point total in five games. And it wasn't because they shot the ball poorly necessarily, but rather, they failed to take care of the basketball, as they committed 18 turnovers to just 19 team assists. Nevertheless, while the loss ended a four-game winning streak, the Hawks will still enter the playoffs with plenty of momentum.

In their regular season finale, the host Utah Jazz took down the San Antonio Spurs, 101-97.

The Jazz (51-31) will finish the season with the fourth seed in the Western Conference and a tie for the league's fifth-best record.  On Wednesday, they finished out their strong season on a high note, shooting over 50 percent and dealing a loss to the second-seeded Spurs.  Star center Rudy Gobert once again made a big impact, scoring 13 points, shooting 5-of-9, and coming down with nine rebounds.  The high scorer for the team was All-Star forward Gordon Hayward, who had only 14 points but earned them in just 22 minutes of playtime.  

San Antonio (61-21) will see no real consequences for losing the game on Wednesday, as it has been locked into the second seed for weeks.  Still, coach Greg Popovich played All-Star forward LaMarcus Aldridge for over 34 minutes in the game, allowing him to total a game-high 18 points.  It was a relatively mediocre night for the Spurs on Wednesday, as the team turned it over 15 times and made only eight three-pointers.  The team likely won't sweat the four-point loss, though; San Antonio is finishing the season with the number one defense and the number seven offense in the NBA, and holds the second-best record of any team in the association.

The host Los Angeles Lakers blew out the Sacramento Kings, 115-95, in the final game of the regular season.  

The Clippers (51-31) secured home court advantage in their first playoff series with their win on Wednesday.
