The blowout was a major occasion for LA, as it saw veteran Paul Pierce step on the court for the final time in the regular season.  Pierce saw just one minute of action after he enjoyed a fourth quarter earlier in the week in which he passed John Havlicek for 15th on the all-time scoring list.  The younger Clippers, meanwhile, won in emphatic fashion.  Six players scored in double figures as the team shot almost 52 percent from the field.  Center DeAndre Jordan led the team with 18 points, 17 rebounds, and four blocks.  

The Kings (32-50) closed what was a season of massive organizational change with a blowout loss, though the team was in no need of a win on Wednesday.  Sacramento should be looking at two lottery picks in the upcoming NBA draft after trading center DeMarcus Cousins and missing the Western Conference playoffs.  The Kings' future looked bright despite the loss on Wednesday, though, as rookie Buddy Hield continued to play well.  Hield scored 16 points to go with six rebounds and four assists.  Sophomore Willie Cauley-Stein added strong play of his own, finishing with 19 points, 14 rebounds, and six assists.

The host Golden State Warriors took down the Los Angeles Lakers in their season finale on Wednesday, 109-94.

Golden State (67-15) has now won at least 67 games in three consecutive seasons, good for the league's best record once again.  The Warriors finished their season strong, winning 15 of their final 16.  Recently-injured superstar Kevin Durant played his third game since returning from injury on Wednesday and looked very much like himself, scoring 29 points on 11-of-16 shooting along with eight rebounds and five assists.  It was a fairly typical Warriors win, as the team dominated every area of the game.  Golden State finished with a 14-rebound advantage, made 12 three-pointers, and dished out 28 team assists.  They will be gearing up to play Portland in the first round of the playoffs.

Los Angeles (26-56) will finish the season with the league's third-worst record.  The Lakers will enter the offseason in a lofty position, as there is a 56 percent chance that they will end up ceding their first-round draft pick to Philadelphia based on the results of the draft lottery.  LA needs its pick to land in the top 3 to maintain ownership.  On Wednesday, the team saw a defeat that was a microcosm of their season.  The team struggled to ever truly find its groove, turning the ball over 18 times and trailing by double digits for the majority of the game.  However, five players did manage to score in double figures.

The visiting New Orleans Pelicans squeaked by the Portland Trail Blazers in their season finale on Wednesday, 103-100.

New Orleans (34-48) allowed their two All-Star big men, Anthony Davis and DeMarcus Cousins, to rest on Wednesday.  The team still played strong basketball, seeing its young players step up to fill the void.  Rookie big man Cheick Diallo led the team with a career-high 16 rebounds in 29 minutes of play.  He added 12 points on 4-of-5 shooting.  The team played extremely well on the defensive end, pressuring the Blazers into numerous turnovers.  The Pelicans ended with 13 steals on the night.  The Pelicans did not make the Western Conference playoffs and will be ceding their first-round pick to the Sacramento Kings unless it lands in the top three.  

Portland (41-41) rested its own star players in preparation for the playoffs.  Guards Damian Lillard and C.J. McCollum each sat, paving way for bench players and prospects to dominate the game.  Backup point guard Shabazz Napier enjoyed a career night, scoring a game-high 25 points on 10-of-18 shooting.  Third-year big man Noah Vonleh also had a strong night, finishing with a game and career-high 19 rebounds along with 12 points to complete a double-double.  The Blazers will be facing the league-best Golden State Warriors in round one of the playoffs.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 103-76, at Philips Arena on Tuesday night.

The Hawks (43-28) came into Tuesday's contest knowing they held their fate in their own hands with respect to the fifth seed in the Eastern Conference. With a victory over a short-handed Hornets (36-46) squad that had nothing except spoiler aspirations remaining, Atlanta was guaranteed the spot. They made sure to take care of business from early on, jumping out to a 38-26 first-quarter lead and expanding their advantage to 63-44 by halftime. With the double-digit edge, no Hawks starter had to play more than 26 minutes and an eight-man second unit combined for 49 points. Atlanta posted a 51.9 percent success rate from the field while limiting Charlotte to 33 percent.

The Hornets bench also had a productive night and Jeremy Lamb actually led all scorers on the night with 21 points, which he supplemented with five rebounds, one assist and two steals. Briante Weber and Treveon Graham contributed 10 points apiece off the second unit as well, with the former adding three assists and one steal and the latter supplying four rebounds, one assist and two steals. Michael Kidd-Gilchrist matched their scoring total and provided six rebounds, one assist and one steal. Marvin Williams totaled seven points, six rebounds  and two steals.

Dwight Howard led the way for Atlanta with a 19-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included one assist and one block. Paul Millsap was next with 10 points and seven rebounds. Ersan Ilyasova matched Millsap's scoring total off the bench and added six boards and two assists. Tim Hardaway, Jr. offered nine points, five rebounds and three assists. Dennis Schroder had a near double-double of eight points, nine assists, three rebounds and one steal. Taurean Prince also had eight points and complemented them with one rebound, one assist and one steal. Kent Bazemore and Mike Muscala had matching eight-point contributions off the bench as well.

The Hornets have wrapped up their regular season, while the Hawks wrap up theirs in Indiana against the Pacers on Wednesday evening.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves, 100-98, at Target Center on Tuesday. 

In a game that meant very little for both teams, they left it all on the floor in this close-fought battle. Victor Oladipo was the hero, as he hit a game-winning jumper with six seconds left to boost the Thunder to a win. There were seven ties and 18 lead changes in total, as this game was within a five-point margin for the final 18 minutes. Rebounding was the decisive statistic, with Oklahoma City winning that battle, 54-35. Bench production was big for the Thunder as well, as they outscored the Timberwolves bench, 38-20.

The Thunder (47-34) played their first game without Russell Westbrook and they escaped with an impressive victory. Oladipo was the star, as he tallied 20 points, nine rebounds and six assists. Domantas Sabonis started and totaled 19 points, nine rebounds and three assists. Steven Adams accrued 10 points, eight rebounds, two steals and two blocks. 

The Timberwolves (31-50) are one of few teams who continue to play their starters, as these losses will ultimately help their youngsters grow. Karl-Anthony Towns led the way for Minnesota, as he accumulated 26 points and 12 rebounds. Gorgui Dieng finished second on the team, amassing 19 points, eight rebounds, three assists and two steals. Andrew Wiggins collected 18 points, three rebounds, four assists and two steals. Ricky Rubio provided 14 points and 10 assists.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the Dallas Mavericks, 109-91, at American Airlines Center on Tuesday. 

This game was meaningless in terms of playoffs, but it secured the season series win for the Nuggets. Shooting was key, with Denver hitting 49 percent of their shots, while holding Dallas to under 40 percent from the field. The Nuggets also took care of the boards, winning the rebounding differential, 53-42. Denver also got some nice production out of their bench, outscoring the Mavericks bench, 47-34.

The Nuggets (39-42) just got knocked out of the playoffs in their most recent loss, but they're still fighting hard to get closer to .500. Gary Harris was the player of the game, as he collected 20 points, eight rebounds and eight assists. Jamal Murray started at point guard and accrued 10 points, two rebounds and 10 assists. Mason Plumlee finished with 16 points and nine rebounds. Malik Beasley led the bench with 16 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals. Denver's last game will be on Wednesday, when they take on the Oklahoma City Thunder on the road.

The Mavericks (32-49) have now lost five-straight games by at least 11 points, as they can't wait for the season to end. Dirk Nowitzki led the way for Dallas, as he totaled 21 points, eight rebounds and three blocks. J.J. Barea accrued 13 points, four rebounds and nine assists. Yogi Ferrell provided 10 points, five rebounds and three assists. The Mavericks will play the Memphis Grizzlies on Wednesday for their final game of the season.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the New Orleans Pelicans 108-96 Tuesday at Staples Center. 

The supposedly tanking Lakers (26-55) have now won five straight games following Tuesday nights's wire-to-wire performance, as after the home team was losing for majority of the first quarter until Larry Nance hit a three-pointer at the buzzer that put them up 26-25. From that point on, the Lakers never lost the lead and continued to build on the lead until the final buzzer. In what was likely his final game at Staples Center, Metta World Peace led the team in scoring with 18 points on 7-of-17 shooting in just 25 minutes. In all, Los Angeles had six different players score in double figures, as they have now scored at least 100 points in seven of their last eight games. The five game winning streak gives them plenty of momentum heading into their season finale against the Warriors on Wednesday. 

As for the Pelicans (33-48), they've been trending in the complete opposite direction and Tuesday's performance was yet another example, as the loss was the team's fifth straight. This is the second straight game they have played without both DeMarcus Cousins and Anthony Davis, and New Orleans has missed their production immensely. However, in their absence Tuesday, rookie Cheick Diallo emerged off the bench for a game-high 19 points and 11 rebounds in 27 points for what was his second double-double of the season. Jrue Holiday and Alexis Ajinca each added 14 points, but in the end, the Pelicans lacked the necessary star power to overcome the streaking Lakers. New Orleans will have one last opportunity Wednesday to end their losing streak when they take on the Trail Blazers in Portland.

The host Sacramento Kings steamrolled the Phoenix Suns on Tuesday, 129-104.  

Sacramento (32-49) enjoyed perhaps its best and most promising outing of the season on Tuesday as the team earned a blowout win.  An incredible eight players scored in double digits as the Kings rode their offense to an easy victory.  The Kings saw a career-high 30 points from rookie Buddy Hield, who became just the second member of the 2016 draft class to score 30 after teammate Skal Labissiere did the same a month earlier.  It was simply a beautiful night on the offensive end for Sacramento, as the team shot almost 52 percent from the floor while dishing out 28 assists.  Veteran point guard Ty Lawson helped run the offense with an impressive 22 points, 12 assists, and 11 rebounds, good for his first triple-double of the 2016-17 season.  

Phoenix (24-58) clinched the league's second-worst record with the loss.  While that may be good news for their lottery pick, the team's play on Tuesday was anything but positive.  The Suns shot only 37 percent from the field and 58 percent from the free-throw line.  Phoenix's own rookie had an impressive game, as Tyler Ulis dropped 27 points and dished out six assists.  However, Ulis was not nearly enough to get the job done on Tuesday.  The team was manhandled in just about every aspect of the game, including rebounding, where Sacramento held a 55-47 advantage.  The loss was the last game of Phoenix's season.

Sacramento will conclude its season in Los Angeles on Wednesday against the Clippers.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 120-111, at Wells Fargo Center on Monday night.

The Pacers (41-40) came in knowing they needed to simply keep winning in order to assure themselves of a playoff berth. However, they knew not to underestimate the Sixers (28-53), who'd given many teams a difficult time, particularly at home. Indiana's best players ensured that there was no letdown, with Paul George leading the way with 27 points, five assists, two rebounds, two steals and one block. The Pacers jumped out to a 35-20 lead in the first quarter and although Philadelphia made up ground the rest of the way, Indiana's 57.6 percent shooting and 44-33 rebounding advantage helped secure victory.

Thaddeus Young followed with 20 points, eight rebounds, three assists and one steal. Myles Turner contributed an 18-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included an assist, four blocks and two steals. Jeff Teague supplied 15 points, six assists, two boards and two steals. Kevin Seraphin led the second unit with 17 points, six rebounds and one steal.

Timothe Luwawu-Cabarrot paced the Sixers with 24 points, five rebounds, three assists and one steal. Richaun Holmes followed with 17 points, six rebounds, two assists and one steal. Alex Poythress and Nik Stauskas followed with bench-leading 15-point efforts, with the former adding a rebound and a steal and the latter registering two assists. T.J. McConnell filled out the stat sheet with 12 points, eight assists, five rebounds and three steals. Dario Saric matched McConnell's scoring total and supplemented it with six rebounds, three assists, two steals and one block.

The Pacers close out the season at home on Wednesday versus the Atlanta Hawks, while the Sixers head to New York to do battle with the Knicks on Wednesday evening as well.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 114-105, at TD Garden on Monday evening. 

The Celtics (52-29) knew that they needed to win out their last two games in order to have a shot at the top seed in the Eastern Conference. With the news coming out earlier in the day that the Cavaliers had opted to rest both LeBron James and Kyrie Irving on Monday night versus the Heat, Boston had even a bit extra motivation to ensure they took care of business against the dangerous Nets (20-61). They came smoking out of the gates, building a 28-13 first-quarter lead and a 58-40 edge by halftime. Although the Nets made things interesting with a 55-point second half, the home team ultimately prevailed with balanced offense that included a pair of double-digit scoring efforts off the bench.

Jeremy Lin led the way for Brooklyn with a 26-point, 12-assist double-double that also included four assists and one block. Brook Lopez was right behind him with 25 points, seven rebounds, two assists and one block. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson managed a 17-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included three assists, four steals and two blocks. Caris LeVert totaled 12 points, three rebounds, two assists and one block. Justin Hamilton led the second unit with 11 points, four rebounds, one steal and one block.

Isaiah Thomas spearheaded Boston with 27 points, four rebounds, three assists and one steal. Al Horford pitched in with 19 points, eight boards, four assists, one steal and one block. Avery Bradley supplied 18 points, five rebounds and two assists. Jae Crowder filled out the stat sheet with 11 points, eight rebounds, six assists, two blocks and one steal. Marcus Smart led the bench with 13 points, six assists, two rebounds, one steal and one block. Kelly Olynyk was solid as a reserve as well with 11 points, six rebounds and three assists.

The Nets finish up the season on Wednesday night against the Bulls in Chicago, while the Celtics remain home to tangle with the Milwaukee Bucks on Wednesday evening as well.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 89-79, at BMO Harris Bradley Center on Monday evening. 

The Bucks (42-39) came in looking to put a couple of wins together before the postseason in order to have some momentum heading in to the second season. They drew a good matchup with which to accomplish that goal, as the Hornets (36-45) announced earlier in the day that Kemba Walker (knee) would sit out the remaining two games of the regular season. Without their superstar guard, Charlotte was considerably challenged to generate offense, and finished the night with just 40.7 percent shooting from the field and 27.8 percent from three-point range. Milwaukee countered with respective 45.5 and 57.1 percent success rates and also won the rebounding battle by a 45-39 margin.

Michael Kidd-Gilchrist served as the Hornets' leading scorer on the night with 13 points, which he complemented with five rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. Treveon Graham and Jeremy Lamb followed with matching 12-point efforts off the bench. Graham only added two steals but Lamb also provided four rebounds, one assist and one steal. Nicolas Batum generated 11 points, eight assists, five rebounds, four steals and one block. Cody Zeller registered nine points, six rebounds, one assist and one block, while Marvin Williams posted a modest five points, four boards, one assist and one block. 

Tony Snell and Greg Monroe led the Bucks with matching 16-point efforts from the starting five and bench, respectively. Snell supplied two assists and two steals alongside his scoring, while Monroe also tallied nine rebounds, three assists and one steal. Khris Middleton totaled 15 points, six boards and six assists. Giannis Antetokounmpo compiled a 10-point, 11-rebound, 10-assist triple-double that also included a block. Malcolm Brogdon managed five points, four boards and three assists.

The Hornets wrap up their season Tuesday night in Atlanta versus the Hawks, while the Bucks finish up in Boston against the Celtics on Wednesday night.

The Miami Heat defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 124-121, in overtime at American Airlines Arena on Monday. 

These are two teams on different ends of the playoff spectrum, as they left it all on the floor in this overtime thriller. It took a big comeback for Miami to send this one into overtime, as they overcame an 11-point deficit in the fourth quarter to send it to an extra session. Tyler Johnson was the hero, as he hit four-straight free-throws in the final minute of OT to take the lead and eventually win. There were nine ties and 15 lead changes in total in this overtime thriller. The assist-to-turnover ratio was the key for Miami, as they recorded nine more assists than Cleveland, while committing eight less turnovers. The Heat also dominated down low, outscoring the Cavaliers in the paint, 50-32.

The Cavaliers (51-30) had to play this game without LeBron James and Kyrie Irving, but their secondary players put in a monster effort. Deron Williams was spectacular in a fill-in role, accumulating 35 points, seven rebounds and nine assists. Kevin Love totaled 25 points and 10 rebounds before fouling out in overtime. Channing Frye started and amassed 21 points and seven rebounds. Kyle Korver was the only bench player with more than four points, as he dropped 18 points and eight boards. Cleveland's final game will be on Wednesday, when they host the Toronto Raptors. 

The Heat (40-41) needed to win this game keep to their playoff hopes alive and they pulled out this nail biter to live another day. Tyler Johnson led the way for Miami, as he provided 24 points, five rebounds and four assists off the bench. Hassan Whiteside was equally as good, accruing 21 points, 18 rebounds and two blocks. James Johnson collected 16 points and nine assists, while Josh Richardson totaled 19 points, six rebounds, four assists and five steals. Miami's final game will be on Wednesday against the Washington Wizards.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the Orlando Magic, 122-75, at United Center on Monday. 

Chicago needed this game to keep their playoff hopes alive and they ended this one early in a dominating effort. In fact, the Bulls held at least an 18-point lead for the final three quarters, in addition to leading by at least 30 for the entire fourth quarter. All the statistics were lopsided, as Chicago shot 54 percent from the field, while holding Orlando to just 35 percent on their end. The Bulls also dominated the rebounding differential, winning that battle, 54-37. Orlando really struggled from long range too, hitting just 5-of-27 from three-point range, while Chicago went 12-of-26.

The Magic (28-53) had a tough task here against a motivated Bulls team and this ended up being one of their ugliest losses of the season. Nikola Vucevic was a bright spot for Orlando, as he tallied 14 points, 10 rebounds and two assists. Aaron Gordon finished with 10 points, six rebounds and two assists. Elfrid Payton accumulated 11 points, seven rebounds and four assists. Bismack Biyombo played well off the bench, totaling seven points, seven rebounds, two steals and two blocks. The Magic's next and final game is on Wednesday against the Detroit Pistons. 

The Bulls (40-41) were tied for the eighth-seed in the east coming into this game, so to say this win was crucial would be a drastic understatement. Jerian Grant started for Rajon Rondo and accrued 17 points, 11 assists and two steals. Jimmy Butler matched those 17 points, adding five rebounds, three assists and three steals to his tally. Robin Lopez led the team, as he amassed 18 points and eight rebounds. Nikola Mirotic collected 16 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals. The Bulls have a great matchup in their final game, as they host the Brooklyn Nets on Wednesday.

The Washington Wizards defeated the Detroit Pistons 105-101 Monday at Palace in Auburn Hills. 

The Wizards (49-32) came into Monday's contest undermanned, as both John Wall (thigh) and Otto Porter (back) were ruled inactive, and head coach Scott Brooks said that his regular starters were going to play limited minutes. That was until Bradley Beal and Markieff Morris decided to carry the team anyway, as the two combined for over half of Washington's points in the victory. Beal was hitting from all over the floor and finished with a game-high 33 points on 13-of-20 shooting in 33 minutes. Meanwhile, in just 27 minutes, Morris managed to record 20 points on 9-of-16 shooting from the field and eight rebounds. The Wizards opened the game up early, leading by 13 points after the first quarter, and while the Pistons (37-44) managed to creep their way back in, Beal managed to make enough plays down the stretch to hold them off. 

Detroit's loss ended what was a two-game winning streak, but the team has still lost 11 of their last 15 games. They were led Monday night by Tobias Harris off the bench, who scored a team-high 22 points in 31 minutes as a reserve. He led the way for a bench mob that accounted for 55 of the team's 101 points. Ish Smith managed to put together yet another nice performance at point guard, scoring 16 points and dishing out nine assists, and while the Pistons managed to make more field goals and three-point shots than their counterparts, the difference ended up being at the free throw line, where Detroit managed to attempt just five shots compared to Washington hitting 14-of-16 from the stripe. 

Up next, in the final game of the season for both teams Wednesday, the Wizards will travel to Miami to take on the Heat, while the Pistons will finish up in Orlando against the Magic.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the San Antonio Spurs 99-98 Monday at Moda Center. 

After a game that was close and hard-fought throughout, the chances of the Trail Blazers (41-40) -- who rested Damian Lillard, C.J. McCollum and Allen Crabbe now that they've locked up the No. 8 seed --  winning was starting to look slim. With just seven seconds left and up by one, the visiting Spurs (61-20) had the ball and were a pair of made free throws away from going to overtime at worst. However, a Kyle Anderson turnover gave Portland one last chance. They took advantage, as a near turnover from Shabazz Napier turned into a wind open layup at the buzzer for Noah Vonleh. The Trail Blazers notched their third straight victory and their eighth straight at home. 

Portland was lead by a career-best night from Napier, who started at point guard in place of Lillard. Napier finished with a career-high 32 points 9-of-20 shooting from the field and 10-of-11 shooting from the free throw line. Each of the Trail Blazers' five starters managed to score in double figures, and those five ended up doing the heavy lifting for an undermanned team, as they combined scored 88 of the team's 99 points Monday night. In fact, the three players that came off the bench combined to shoot a horrid 4-of-27 (15 percent) from the field. 

As for the Spurs, they had all regular rotation players active and healthy, but head coach Gregg Popovich elected to limit the minutes of his key players. Most notably, Kawhi Leonard played just 20 minutes and was absent during the final stretch of the game. Yet, somehow, the MVP-candidate managed to score a game-high 18 points as he shot 8-of-11 from the field. No other San Antonio player managed to score more than 12 points, as majority of the bench struggled to get anything going despite most of them playing more minutes than usual. 

Up next, the Spurs, who have now lost three of their last five games, will travel to Utah for their season finale Wednesday, while the Trail Blazers will play their final game at home Wednesday against the Pelicans.

The host Los Angeles Clippers blew out the Houston Rockets on Monday, 125-96.

LA (50-31) remains in a close battle with Utah to earn home-court advantage in their first round series.  Monday's game saw an easy win for the Clippers, as they held a double-digit lead for almost the entirety of the second half.  Seven Clippers players scored in double digits, as the game proved to be a well-rounded team victory.  Superstar point guard Chris Paul led the team with 19 points and dished out nine assists on the night.  The team finally appeared to be healthy and firing on all cylinders, as the Clippers ended with a 49-41 rebounding advantage and shot over 50 percent from the field on the night.  It was also a historic night for veteran forward Paul Pierce, who scored 10 points to pass John Havlicek for 15th on the all-time scoring list.  

Houston (54-27) had a rough night on Monday, starting with superstar James Harden.  The MVP contender shot just 2-of-9 from the field and 9-of-14 at the free-throw line while committing five fouls and five turnovers in only 24 minutes of play.  That was roughly how the night went for most of the Rockets' lineup, as the team finished shooting only 39 percent from the field.  Rebounding also played a role in the blowout, as Houston was at an eight-rebound disadvantage by the night's end.  

The Clippers will host the Kings on Wednesday, while Houston will host the Timberwolves.

The visiting Utah Jazz took down the Golden State Warriors on Monday, 105-99.

Utah (50-31) reached a major milestone with its 50th win on Monday, its first 50-win season since 2010.  Thanks to the win, the Jazz became just the fifth team in NBA history to move from the 20s to the 30s to the 40s to the 50s in the win column in consecutive seasons.  Monday's upset win came thanks in large part to strong play from star center Rudy Gobert.  Gobert led the team with a whopping 18 rebounds and also posted 17 points.  Overall, the night proved to be a stellar one for Utah on the offensive end.  The team drained 13 three-pointers and saw six players score in double figures.

Golden State (66-15) has locked up the top spot in the Western Conference and thus has little to play for during its remaining games.  The Warriors did, however, lose a league-best 14-game win streak after falling to Utah on Monday.  Recently-returned superstar Kevin Durant posted a 16-point, 10-rebound double-double in just his second game back from a knee injury.  Reigning MVP Steph Curry, meanwhile, led the team in scoring with an impressive 28 points.  The team chose to sit All-Star shooting guard Klay Thompson on Monday.  With the loss, the Warriors fell to 1-3 on the season without Thompson in the lineup.

In their final games of the season on Wednesday, the Jazz will host the Spurs, while the Warriors will host the Lakers.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the New York Knicks, 110-97, at Madison Square Garden on Sunday afternoon.

The Raptors (50-31) checked into Sunday's game with plenty of motivation for a win, considering that a victory would clinch them the third seed in the Eastern Conference. Standing in their way was a short-handed but feisty Knicks (30-51) squad that had shown some fight recently despite having been long eliminated from playoff contention. Through the first three quarters, New York gave Toronto all they could handle, entering the fourth quarter trailing only 76-75. However, the Raptors turned it on at that point, going on a 12-0 run midway through the period that helped seal the win. DeMar DeRozan once again led the way, turning in a remarkable 35-point effort on 11-of-15 shooting from the field, and complementing the scoring with a pair of rebounds. That led to a stellar 52.6 percent success rate from the field for the visitors on their way to their 22nd road win of the campaign.

Kyle Lowry was an ideal complement to DeRozan's fireworks, turning in an efficient 17-point, 11-assist double-double that also included seven rebounds, three steals and a block. Lowry was particularly effective from three-point range, draining four of nine attempts from behind the arc. Patrick Patterson turned in a bench-leading 15 points, which he supplemented with three rebounds, one assist and one steal. Serge Ibaka contributed 12 points and four rebounds. Jonas Valanciunas had a modest outing, posting six points, seven boards and one steal. Jakob Poeltl (eight points, seven rebounds) and P.J. Tucker (eight points, seven rebounds, one assist and one steal) were productive as reserves as well.

Willy Hernangomez led the way for New York with 24 points, 11 rebounds, five assists and three steals. Courtney Lee followed with 14 points, three assists and one steal. Mindauguas Kuzminskas led the bench with 12 points and one rebound. Ron Baker provided 11 points, eight rebounds, eight assists and one steal. Justin Holiday drew another start and compiled 10 points, five rebounds, five assists, one steal and one block. 

The Raptors head to Cleveland to take on the Cavaliers on Wednesday evening to close out the season, while the Knicks are home against the Sixers in their season finale on Wednesday night as well.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 126-125, in overtime at Philips Arena on Sunday. 

In this potential playoff preview, Cleveland suffered an incredible collapse. In fact, they led by 26 headed into the fourth quarter, but allowed Atlanta to outscore them 44-18 in the final quarter to send it to overtime. Despite the Cavaliers leading for most of the overtime, Atlanta finished the game on a 15-9 run to comeback yet again and win. Scoring in the paint was the only real advantage for the Hawks, as they won that battle, 58-48. Their bench was huge as well, outscoring Cleveland's bench, 44-16.

The Cavaliers (52-28) simply fell apart in this game and it'll go down as their worst loss of the season. LeBron James picked up his 15th triple-double of the year though, collecting 32 points, 16 rebounds and 10 assists before fouling out in overtime. Kyrie Irving led the team in scoring, accruing 45 points, two rebounds and nine assists. Kevin Love finished with 11 points, 15 rebounds and five assists. Channing Frye started and totaled 12 points and eight rebounds. On deck for the Cavaliers is a road matchup versus the Miami Heat on Monday.

The Hawks (41-39) had one of their greatest comebacks in franchise history here, as they've now handed the Cavaliers back-to-back devastating losses. Paul Millsap returned to his starting role to provide 22 points, nine rebounds and two assists. Dwight Howard amassed 19 points, five rebounds and two assists on 9-of-12 shooting. Tim Hardaway Jr. accumulated 21 points, nine rebounds and four assists. Kent Bazemore was a nice spark off the bench, contributing 13 points, two rebounds, four assists and four steals. Mike Muscala also played well off the bench, dropping 12 points, five rebounds and four assists. Atlanta will look to keep rolling on Tuesday against the Charlotte Hornets.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the host Denver Nuggets, 106-105, at Pepsi Center on Sunday. 

All the talk in this game will be around Russell Westbrook and rightfully so. Not only did he set the record for triple-doubles in a season in this win, he hit the game-winner at the buzzer from nearly 40-feet out. It took a huge comeback to pull out the victory too, as they outscored Denver, 25-14, in the fourth quarter. Rebounding was the difference for Oklahoma City, as they won that battle, 54-42.  

The Thunder (46-34) are locked into the six-seed in the west, but this will be a game Oklahoma City fans remember forever. Westbrook picked up his 42nd triple-double of the season, which passed the all-time record set by Oscar Robertson. He finished with 50 points, 16 rebounds and 10 assists. He actually scored the final 18 points for Oklahoma City and hit the game-winning three from just inside halfcourt. Steven Adams was the only other starter in double figures, totaling 10 points and 10 rebounds. Enes Kanter was a nice spark off the bench, providing 15 points and eight rebounds. Oklahoma City's next game is on Tuesday against the Minnesota Timberwolves. 

The Nuggets (38-42) needed this win to keep their season alive and they prevailed despite Westbrook's record-setting day. Danilo Gallinari did all he could for Denver, as he tallied 34 points, 10 rebounds and three assists. Nikola Jokic finished with 23 points, six rebounds and three assists. Wilson Chandler amassed 17 points and 10 rebounds. Emmanuel Mudiay played well off the bench, dropping 14 points, five rebounds and three assists. That marks the end of Denver's playoff pursuit, as they'll play the Dallas Mavericks for their next game on Tuesday.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the Dallas Mavericks, 124-111, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Sunday. 

These are two teams battling for lottery positioning and this win for Phoenix may not be what management wanted. In any case, the Suns really dominated in the first and third quarters, outscoring the Mavericks, 76-49. Shooting was the difference in the game, with Phoenix shooting 55 percent from the field, 42 percent from three-point range and 88 percent from the free-throw line. Dallas shot just 42 percent from the field, 36 percent from three-point range and 68 percent from the free-throw line. The Suns also dominated down low, outscoring the Mavericks in the paint, 56-34.

The Mavericks (32-48) played this game without Harrison Barnes and Seth Curry, as they simply didn't have enough in the arsenal to compete with the Suns. Yogi Ferrell led the way for Dallas, as he accrued 21 points, four rebounds and four assists. Dwight Powell had a nice game off the bench, providing 21 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals. Dorian Finney-Smith finished with six points, 11 rebounds and three assists. 

The Suns (24-57) had lost 13 of 14 headed into this game, so a win is a good confidence booster going forward. Tyler Ulis was the player of the game, as he collected 20 points, three rebounds and 10 assists. Devin Booker totaled 21 points, two rebounds and three assists. Alex Len recorded a double-double, amassing 14 points, 10 rebounds and two blocks. T.J, Warren totaled 21 points and seven rebounds, going a perfect 8-of-8 from the field. Dragan Bender had one of the best games of his rookie season, producing nine points, eight rebounds and three assists off the bench.

The visiting Houston Rockets took down the Sacramento Kings on Sunday, 135-128.

Houston (54-26) saw another win in what is turning out to be a very successful season.  Superstar guard James Harden led the team on Sunday, recording his 12th triple-double of the season including 35 points.  However, he also struggled with ball control, committing 10 turnovers on the night.  The Rockets continued their stellar three-point shooting, knocking down 18 three-pointers on the night and shooting almost 57 percent from the field.  They also shot a respectable 27-of-31 from the free-throw line.

Sacramento (31-49) is surprisingly having a bit of a late-season renaissance, as the team is now 5-6 in its last 11 games.  The team put forward a balanced effort on Sunday, as they saw seven players score in double figures.  Two Kings tied for a team high with 20 points.  Veteran point guard Ty Lawson was one of the two, scoring 20 and dishing out 11 assists.  Rookie Skal Labissiere, meanwhile, scored 20 points on a stellar 8-of-10 from the field.  As a whole, the Kings shot almost 50 percent from the field, but hit only eight three-pointers on the night.  

The Rockets will visit the Clippers on Monday, while Sacramento will host the Suns on Tuesday.

The visiting Detroit Pistons took down the Memphis Grizzlies on Sunday, 103-90.

Detroit (37-43) came off a tough stretch of games, having dropped seven of their last 10 going into the Sunday's matchup.  The Pistons looked top-notch on Sunday, though, as they poured in 14 three-pointers on the night.  Detroit also excelled on the glass, holding a 46-30 advantage in the rebounding column.  The leading rebounder was All-Star center Andre Drummond, who pulled down 11 boards.  Six Pistons finished the game with double-figure scoring, and the team ended up shooting over 47 percent from the field as a whole.

Memphis (43-38) is locked into the seventh seed and will play San Antonio in the first round of the playoffs.  As such, Sunday's off night was not too much of a cause for concern.  The Grizzlies enjoyed plenty of rest, as no player played more than 27 minutes.  Point guard Mike Conley helped the team stay in the game, scoring 15 points in 23 minutes of play.  Despite the low play time for their starters, the team's "grit-and-grind" style continued, as they came away with an impressive 12 steals on the night.  

Detroit will host the Wizards on Monday, while Memphis will host the Mavericks on Wednesday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves 110-109 at Staples Center on Sunday. 

The Lakes (24-55) held on for victory over the Timberwolves (31-48) despite Karl-Anthony Towns and Andrew Wiggins combined 81 points. The Minnesota duo both were shooting lights out and keeping their team in the game, one in which they opted to only run four players deep on the bench. Towns and Wiggins played 41 minutes and 38 minutes, respectively, which were the two highest totals for either team. The Lakers jumped out to an eight point lead at the end of the first quarter, but the efficient shooting and non-existent answer to stopping Towns on the block and in the paint made for a dramatic finish. With :32 remaining the in the fourth quarter, Julius Randle dunked home two points that brought the Lakers within two points of the leading Timberwolves, while Randle also rebounded the Metta-Wolrd Peace missed three and kicked it to D'Angelo Russell, who drained the game winning three-pointer with :02 left. 

Towns finished with 40 points, 21 rebounds, four assists, one steal and one block on 17-of-22 shooting. Wiggins totaled 41 points on 13-of-26 shooting, including 2-of-5 from behind the arc. 

D'Angelo Russell was not nearly as efficient as his opponents, but did finish with 16 points, four assists and four rebounds, while Randle added 13 points, eight boards, two assists, one steal and one block in his 28 minutes of work. 

Both teams play on Tuesday, as the Timberwolves host the Oklahoma City Thunder, while the Lakers host the New Orleans Pelicans.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Chicago Bulls, 107-106, at Barclays Center on Saturday afternoon.

Someone apparently forgot to tell the Nets (20-60) that they have nothing left to play for, as they've been particularly impressive in the second half of the season. One of their recent trademarks has been giving quality teams a very difficult time, even those with plenty of motivation for playoff positioning. The Bulls (39-41) were the latest team to learn that lesson the hard way, as they fell victim to a Brooklyn fourth-quarter comeback and dropped a one-point decision that could jeopardize their playoff hopes. Spencer Dinwiddie's two free throws with 13 seconds remaining snapped a 103-103 tie, and Jimmy Butler's three-pointer with one second left came too little too late for Chicago. While the Bulls shot better than the Nets and also won the rebounding battle by a 52-44 margin, they also committed 17 turnovers, contributing to their demise.

Butler led the way for the visitors with 33 points, seven rebounds and four assists. Robin Lopez tallied 16 points, eight rebounds and one block. Jerian Grant followed with 15 points, five assists, three rebounds, one steal and one block. Dwyane Wade made his return from an elbow injury that was once thought to be season-ending and posted 14 points, seven rebounds, two assists and a block over 25 minutes. Nikola Mirotic rounded out the starting five's night with four points, seven rebounds, two steals and two blocks.

Caris LeVert and Dinwiddie  led the way for Brooklyn with matching 19-point efforts.  LeVert added five rebounds, one assist and one steal while Dinwiddie supplied four assists, three rebounds and two steals. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson generated a 16-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included three assists, three steals and one block. Brook Lopez tallied 13 points, four rebounds, one assist and one block. Jeremy Lin filled out the stat sheet with 12 points, seven assists, six rebounds and three steals.

The Bulls head back home to face the Orlando Magic on Monday night, while the Nets head to Beantown to tangle with the Boston Celtics on Monday evening as well.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 121-114, at Spectrum Center on Saturday afternoon.

The Celtics (51-29) checked into Saturday looking to quickly right the ship after losing their previous two games and falling out of the top spot in the Eastern Conference in the process. While they retained a modest chance of still overtaking the Cavaliers, their overriding purpose in notching a win Saturday was to avoid falling further back in the standings, given that the Toronto Raptors were only 1.5 games behind. Boston was able to accomplish that goal by getting off to a fast start and building a 71-54 halftime lead. However, the Hornets (36-44) mounted a furious comeback in the third and eventually took a seven-point lead in the fourth before the Celtics clawed back to tally their 22nd road win of the season.

Isaiah Thomas led the way for the Celtics with 32 points, six assists, two rebounds and one steal. Al Horford followed with 16 points, seven assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block. Jae Crowder posted a near double-double of 15 points, nine rebounds and three assists. Avery Bradley matched Crowder's scoring total and added six rebounds, four assists and a block. Kelly Olynyk drew the start for Amir Johnson (illness) and registered a 13-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included four assists and one block. Jaylen Brown led the second unit with 10 points and three boards.

Nicolas Batum paced Charlotte with 31 points, which he supplemented with eight rebounds and three assists. Kemba Walker totaled 23 points, eight assists, one rebound and one steal. Jeremy Lamb was next with a bench-leading 17 points, along with five rebounds, one assist and two blocks. Cody Zeller offered 12 points, nine rebounds, two assists and three steals. Michael Kidd-Gilchrist managed eight points, four rebounds, one assist and one block.

The Celtics head back home to face the Brooklyn Nets on Monday night, while the Hornets head to Milwaukee to take on the Bucks on Monday evening as well.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the host Orlando Magic, 127-112, at Amway Center on Saturday evening. 

This marks the third win in a row for the Pacers, who are back in business, after losing four straight. They need everything they can get in order to stay in possession of a playoff spot in the East. They came into this game only one game ahead of the ninth-place Heat, and made sure it will stay that way for now, by winning all four quarters, behind 37 from Paul George. 

The Pacers shot a blistering 59.3 percent from the field and 50 percent from long distance. George led the way with 37 points on 14-of-22 shooting, including 4-of-9 from long range, along with seven rebounds and six assists, in 40 minutes. Myles Turner followed up with 23 points on 10-of-13 shooting, 10 rebounds and two blocks, in 30 minutes. Three other players scored in double digits for the Pacers, including C.J. Miles and Kevin Seraphin, who chipped in 11 each off the bench, while Thaddeus Young added 14 points on 7-of-8 shooting, in 31 minutes. The Pacers head to Philly, where they will take on the 76ers on Monday. 

Meanwhile, Terrence Ross led the Magic, with 29 points on 10-of-17 shooting, including 6-of-11 from downtown. Evan Fournier followed up with 23 points, while Elfrid Payton added 10 points and 10 assists. Aaron Gordon went for 17 points on 7-of-13 shooting, in 37 minutes. The Magic gave up a troublesome 64 points in the paint. They go on to face the Bulls in Chicago on Monday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 90-82, at Wells Fargo Center on Saturday night.

The Bucks (41-39) needed to make sure they took care of their business against the Sixers (28-52), as they checked into Saturday not yet having clinched a playoff spot. Milwaukee got off on the right foot in that regard with a 23-21 first-quarter advantage, but Philadelphia bounced back by taking the second quarter by a 27-19 margin. However, the Bucks gained some distance with an outstanding third quarter in which they held their hosts to 12 points. They turned in a stellar defensive effort overall, limiting the Sixers to success rates of 35.1 percent from the field and 25.8 percent from three-point range.

Giannis Antetokounmpo supplied a 20-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included six assists, three steals and two blocks. Greg Monroe followed with a bench-leading 17 points that he supplemented with five boards, three assists, two steals and one block. Matthew Dellavedova was next with 14 points, three rebounds and three assists. Khris Middleton filled out the stat sheet with eight points, eight rebounds, two assists and three steals. Spencer Hawes was productive as a reserve as well with eight points and two rebounds.

Richaun Holmes led the way for the Sixers with 17 points, 10 rebounds and one block. Dario Saric filled out the stat sheet with 14 points, eight rebounds, four assists and two steals. Timothe Luwawu-Cabarrot managed 12 points, four rebounds, two assists and four steals. T.J. McConnell posted a 10-point, 10-assist double-double that also included two rebounds and three steals. Justin Anderson rounded out a strong night for the starting five with eight points, six boards and two assists.

The Bucks head back home to take on the Charlotte Hornets on Monday evening, while the Sixers remain home to tangle with the Indiana Pacers on Monday night.

The Miami Heat kept their playoff hopes alive with a huge, 106-103, win in Washington, at Verizon Center, on Saturday evening. 

This marked the second game of a back-to-back for the Heat, who left it all on the court and came through with a win to keep their playoff hopes alive. They led by four entering the fourth quarter, where both teams battled, trading the lead multiple times down the stretch. The Heat were down by one when they took a full timeout with 20 seconds left. They set up an isolation play for James Johnson, which worked to perfection as he cruised his way to the rack for an easy layup and the one-point advantage. The Wizards then had a chance to win it with the final possession, however Kelly Oubre Jr. made a poor inbound pass that the Heat easily picked off. Josh Richardson was then fouled and sank two shots at the line, sealing the three-point win. 

Hassan Whiteside came up big, leading the Heat with 30 points on 12-of-19 shooting, along with 12 rebounds, three blocks, two assists and two steals, in 37 minutes. Tyler Johnson followed up with 19 points, while Goran Dragic chipped in 18 points and seven assists. James Johnson came up huge down the stretch, finishing with 15 points, 11 rebounds and five assists, in 37 minutes. The Heat are now tied with the Bulls for eighth place, and one game behind the seventh-place Pacers. They will need to take care of business on Monday, when they play host to the Cavaliers, in order to keep the dream alive. 

Meanwhile, all five starters scored in double digits for Washington, led by Markieff Morris, who finished with 21 points on 9-of-13 shooting.  John Wall and Bradley Beal added 16 points each, while Marcin Gortat double-doubled with 11 points and 11 rebounds. The Wizards head to Detroit to take on the Pistons on Monday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the host San Antonio Spurs, 98-87, at AT&T Center on Saturday. 

These are two teams that have secured playoff berths, but they still fought hard in this potential playoff preview. In fact, there were four ties and 10 lead changes, with neither team leading by more than 14. Los Angeles were in control for most of the game though, leading for over 40 minutes and holding a lead for the entirety of the second half. Shooting was the difference in the game, with the Clippers hitting 50 percent of their shots and the Spurs shooting just 43 percent from the field. Los Angeles also dominated down low, winning the point in the paint differential, 48-32. 

The Clippers (49-31) have now won five-straight games, as they have some serious momentum headed into the postseason. Chris Paul led the way, as he tallied 19 points, eight rebounds and eight assists. DeAndre Jordan totaled 17 points and 17 rebounds. Blake Griffin amassed 18 points and eight rebounds. Jamal Crawford was a nice spark off the bench, dropping 12 points.

The Spurs (61-19) are locked up in the two-seed in the west, but they still lost this game with all their weapons fully healthy. Kawhi Leonard was a bright spot for San Antonio, as he collected 28 points, five rebounds and five assists. LaMarcus Aldridge scored 18 points in 35 minutes. Pau Gasol was the only other Spur in double figures, as he provided 15 points and seven rebounds off the bench.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the Utah Jazz, 101-86, at Moda Center on Saturday.

These are two teams that look poised to reach the postseason, as Portland showed how dangerous they can be. It was a near wire-to-wire win for the Blazers, with Utah maintaining just one lead in the opening two minutes. The first and third quarters is where Portland did their damage, outscoring Utah, 63-38, in those two quarters. Turnovers were the difference in the game, as Portland committed just three of them, while forcing the Jazz to commit 14 on their end. The Blazers also took advantage of the long ball, hitting 13-of-30 from three-point range, while the Jazz went just 6-of-19.

The Jazz (49-31) are now tied with the Los Angeles Clippers for the fourth-seed in the west, as this loss could be devastating for homecourt advantage. Gordon Hayward did all he could for Utah, as he led the way with 21 points, five rebounds and four assists. Rudy Gobert finished with 13 points, 11 rebounds and four blocks The other three starters combined for just eight points. Joe Johnson and Rodney Hood both scored in double figures off the bench. On deck for Utah is a road matchup versus the Golden State Warriors on Monday.

The Trail Blazers (40-40) are now 1.5 games up on the Denver Nuggets for the eighth-seed in the west, as this win got them one step closer to securing a playoff berth. Damian Lillard was the player of the game, as he scored 26 of his career-high 59 points in the first quarter. Lillard did that damage on 18-of-34 shooting, while also adding six rebounds and five assists to his tally. C.J. McCollum struggled, as he accrued nine points, three rebounds and five assists on 4-of-20 from the field.  Maurice Harkless was the only other Blazer in double figures, as he amassed 12 points, three rebounds and three steals. Portland will look to secure that playoff berth on Monday, when they host the San Antonio Spurs for their next game.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the New Orleans Pelicans, 123-101, at Oracle Arena on Saturday.

This was a lopsided matchup on paper and that proved to be true on the court as well. The second half was particularly lopsided, with Golden State leading by at least 20 points for the final 16 minutes. Rebounding was the biggest factor for the Warriors, as they won that battle, 53-34. They were also very efficient, recording 36 assists on 51 percent shooting, while committing just nine turnovers. Free-throw shooting was a factor as well, with Golden State hitting 15-of-16 and New Orleans going just 12-of-19. 

The Pelicans (33-47) played this game without Anthony Davis and DeMarcus Cousins, as they had very little to compete with the best team in the league. Alexis Ajinca got the start at center and led the starters with 17 points and six rebounds. Jrue Holiday accrued 10 points, six rebounds and 10 assists. Jordan Crawford and Quinn Cook played well off the bench, combining for 43 points on 18-of-29 from the field. On deck for New Orleans is a road matchup against the Los Angeles Lakers on Tuesday. 

The Warriors (66-14) have secured the top-spot in the west and wins like this show just how motivated they are. Kevin Durant made his return from a knee injury to accrue 16 points, 10 rebounds and six assists. Klay Thompson led the team, as he scored 20 points to add to his three rebounds and two assists. Ian Clark and Andre Iguodala were huge off the bench, as Clark provided 17 points, four rebounds and three assists, with Iguodala tallying 15 points, five rebounds and five assists. The Warriors will host the Utah Jazz for their next game on Monday.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the host Cleveland Cavaliers, 114-100, at Quicken Loans Arena on Friday. 

Cleveland were expected to win this game easily against a B-team Hawks unit, but Atlanta had other ideas. The game was close throughout the first three quarters, as there were seven ties and 14 lead changes in total. A 21-2 run in the fourth quarter really opened things up for the Hawks, as it gave them a game-high 20-point lead with four minutes remaining. The bench was the difference in the game, with Atlanta's bench outscoring the Cavaliers bench, 55-21. The assists were a decisive statistic too, with Atlanta recording 39 assists to Cleveland's 23. Three-point shooting really let the Cavaliers down, as they went 9-of-36 from downtown, while the Hawks went 16-of-37. 

The Hawks (41-38) played this game without Paul Millsap, Dennis Schroder, Kent Bazemore, and Dwight Howard, but their role players fought hard in this amazing effort. Tim Hardaway Jr. led Atlanta with 22 points, two rebounds and five assists on 9-of-14 shooting. Kris Humphries started and accumulated 12 points, seven rebounds and four assists. Mike Dunleavy was huge off the bench, as he dropped 20 points in just 17 minutes. 

The Cavaliers (51-28) had one of their ugliest performances of the season, as they were outplayed at home by a beleaguered Hawks team. LeBron James led the way for Cleveland, as he collected 28 points, eight rebounds and seven assists. Kevin Love totaled 15 points, 15 rebounds and three assists. Kyrie Irving amassed 18 points and seven assists. Channing Frye got the start and accrued 16 points, five rebounds and two blocks. 

These two teams will have a rematch on Sunday in Atlanta.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Miami Heat, 96-94, at Air Canada Centre on Friday night.

The Raptors (49-31) came in with a playoff berth assured but also seeking to stay locked into the third seed in the Eastern Conference. Meanwhile, the Heat's (38-41) postseason aspirations were in a much more precarious position, as they came into the night hanging on to the seventh seed by a thread. As it turned out, the team with a bit less to lose played with more urgency, as Toronto jumped out to a 26-19 first-quarter lead. Miami did battle back throughout the second and third quarters, setting up a pivotal final 12 minutes. However, the Raptors did just enough to keep the Heat at bay, taking a 94-88 lead with 25 seconds left after a DeMar DeRozan basket. Wayne Ellington gave the visitors hope with a three-pointer, but a pair of DeRozan three-pointers with four seconds remaining gave the home squad a commanding 96-91 advantage.

James Johnson led the way against his former teammates with 22 points, 10 rebounds, three assists, three steals and two blocks. Goran Dragic followed with 18 points, one rebound, one assist and one steal. Hassan Whiteside posted a 12-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included two assists. Ellington matched Whiteside's scoring total off the bench and added one rebound, one assist and one steal. Josh Richardson totaled 10 points, four assists, two rebounds, three steals and one block. Rodney McGruder filled out the stat sheet with nine points, five rebounds and two assists. 

DeRozan paced Toronto with a game-high 38 points, which he supplemented with six boards, two assists, one steal and one block. Cory Joseph followed as a distant second with a bench-leading 14 points, along with four boards, three assists and three steals. Kyle Lowry filled out the stat sheet with 12 points, seven rebounds, six assists and two steals. Serge Ibaka had a near double-double with 11 points, nine rebounds and one block. Jonas Valanciunas mustered a modest nine points but hauled in 10 boards. 

The Heat next head to the Nation's Capital to do battle with the Washington Wizards on Saturday evening, while the Raptors head to New York to tangle with the Knicks on Sunday afternoon.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the New York Knicks, 101-88, at FedEx Forum on Friday night. 

The Grizzlies (43-37) came into Friday's game knowing they were facing a short-handed and likely unmotivated Knicks (30-50) squad, but needing to focus on getting their own house in order prior to the playoffs. Memphis had lost seven of the previous nine games and therefore needed a victory under any circumstance, and accordingly, they were able to take care of business Friday. New York announced that they'd be without Carmelo Anthony for rest purposes, and were already missing Kristaps Porzingis (back) and Derrick Rose (knee). However, their makeshift starting five did put up a valiant effort through three quarters before the home team pulled away with a 31-point fourth period. The Grizzlies enjoyed a rare strong shooting night, tallying a 50.7 percent success rate from the field and 55.6 percent figure from three-point range.

New York was led by Courtney Lee's 16 points, which he supplemented with three rebounds, three assists and one steal. Maurice Ndour followed with 15 points, seven rebounds, three blocks and one steal. Justin Holiday drew the start and put up 12 points, two rebounds, two assists and three steals. Willy Hernangomez provided an 11-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three assists and two steals. Mindaugas Kuzminskas led the second unit with 10 points and one rebound.

Mike Conley paced Memphis with a game-high 31 points, which he complemented with six assists, three rebounds and one steal. Marc Gasol tallied a 16-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three assists and three blocks. Wayne Selden was next with a bench-leading 13 points, two rebounds and two assists. Vince Carter filled out the stat sheet with 12 points, four rebounds, three assists, two blocks and one steal. Tony Allen and JaMychal Green managed matching 10-point efforts, with the former adding four rebounds and the latter hauling in five boards and adding one assist and one block. 

The Knicks head back home to await the Toronto Raptors on Sunday afternoon, while the Grizzlies remain home to face the Detroit Pistons on Sunday evening.

The Detroit Pistons defeated the host Houston Rockets, 114-109, at Toyota Center on Friday. 

This game was much more important for the Pistons than the Rockets and that was evident by this final scoreline. It took a big comeback for Detroit to win, as they outscored Houston, 39-22, in the fourth quarter. Offensive rebounding was a huge factor for the Pistons, as they won that battle, 18-9. Detroit also dominated down low, as they outscored Houston in the paint, 52-38. Efficiency was also key, with the Pistons recording 27 assists while committing just six turnovers. 

The Pistons (36-43) playoff hopes were hanging on a thread coming into this game and this win will keep it alive for the time being. Boban Marjanovic was the player of the game, as he provided 27 points and 12 rebounds on 12-of-18 shooting off Detroit's bench. Ish Smith tallied 20 points, three rebounds and five assists. Henry Ellenson got a rare start and totaled 15 points and 11 rebounds. Tobias Harris accrued 17 points, six rebounds and two assists off the bench. On deck for Detroit is a road matchup against the Memphis Grizzlies on Sunday. 

The Rockets (53-26) have the three-seed locked up in the west and losses like this really don't matter at this point of the season. James Harden did all he could though, as he led Houston with 33 points, nine rebounds and 12 assists. No other starter reached double figures in scoring. Patrick Beverley did play well though, collecting six points, 13 rebounds and five assists. Lou Williams and Eric Gordon led the bench, as they scored 15 points a piece. Houston's next game will be on Sunday, when they play the Sacramento Kings on the road.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the host Dallas Mavericks, 102-89, at American Airlines Center, on Friday evening. 

The Mavs (32-47) started out strong and led, 61-50 at halftime. Despite resting six of their top players, the Spurs (61-18) came out on a mission in the third quarter, where they out-scored the Mavs 25-8, and finished the quarter on a 17-2 run. The Spurs took care of business in the fourth to complete the comeback win. 

LaMarcus Aldridge (rest), Kawhi Leonard (rest), Pau Gasol (rest), Tony Parker (rest), Manu Ginobili (rest) and Danny Green (thigh) were all sidelined, leaving the job up to the Spurs' youngsters and role players. Bryn Forbes led the way for San Antonio, with a career-high 27 points on 10-of-19 shooting, in 29 minutes. Davis Bertans followed up with 19 points, shooting 5-of-9 from long range, in 39 minutes. Dewayne Dedmon chipped in 10 points and 13 rebounds, while David Lee added 16 points and 13 rebounds, off the bench. The Spurs face the second game of a back-to-back, as they play host to the Clippers on Saturday evening. 

Meanwhile, only two players scored in double digits for Dallas. Dwight Powell was the high-point man for the Mavs, with 12 points on 5-of-9 shooting, in 25 minutes off the bench. Yogi Ferrell followed up with 11 points, while Dirk Nowitzki, Nerlens Noel and Harrison Barnes chipped in eight points each. The Mavs' next contest comes on Sunday, when they take on the Suns, in Phoenix.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting New Orleans Pelicans, 122-106, at Pepsi Center on Friday evening. 

Denver led 30-25 after the first quarter, but went into half time up by only one, with the score 51-50. However, the Nuggets came out on a mission in the third quarter, where they poured in 41 points, to amass an 18-point lead heading into the fourth, and cruise to a significant victory in terms of their playoff chase. The Pelicans (33-46) kept Anthony Davis and Jrue Holiday to only 24 minutes each, while DeMarcus Cousins sat out due to a sore achilles, giving the Nuggets (38-41) an extra edge.

Three players topped 20 points for Denver, including Jamal Murray, who led the way with a career-high 30 points on 10-of-14 shooting, in 38 minutes. Nikola Jokic followed up with 23 points, 12 rebounds, five assists and two steals, in 29 minutes, while Gary Harris added 20 points, nine assists, five rebounds and one steal. The Nuggets are now only one game behind the eighth-place Trail Blazers, and will look to inch closer, as they play host to the Thunder on Sunday. 

Meanwhile, Anthony Davis led the Pelicans with 25 points, in 24 minutes. Jordan Crawford poured in 20 points on 10-of-16 shooting, in 30 minutes off the bench, while Alexis Ajinca also came up big off the bench, with 15 points and seven rebounds, in 28 minutes. The only other player to score in double digits for New Orleans was E'Twaun Moore, who chipped in 10 points. The Pelicans face the second game of a back-to-back, as they play in Golden State on Saturday evening.

The Utah Jazz hung on to defeat the visiting Minnesota Timberwolves, 120-113, at Vivint Smart Home Arena, on Friday evening. 

The Timberwolves led by 10 points with 6:50 left in the third quarter, but fell into their bad habit of falling apart late in games. The Jazz dropped 40 points in the third quarter and matched the T-Wolves point-for-point in the fourth, in order to complete the comeback. This marks the Timberwolves' 22nd loss of the season after having led by double digits in the game. This was a big win for the Jazz, who now pull another 0.5 games ahead of the Clippers, building their cushion to one game. 

Gordon Hayward poured in a career-high 39 points on 14-of-22 shooting, in 39 minutes of action, to lead the way for the Jazz. Joe Johnson came up huge in 33 minutes off the bench, with 22 points on 8-of-10 shooting, including 4-of-5 from deep. Rudy Gobert chipped in 16 points, while Derrick Favors added 13 off the bench. The Jazz will be right back in action, as they take on the Trail Blazers in Portland on Saturday evening. 

Meanwhile, Karl-Anthony Towns led the Timberwolves with 32 points on 12-of-21 shooting, along with 13 rebounds, in 32 minutes. Ricky Rubio followed up with 26 points and 12 assists, while Andrew Wiggins added 25 points, but shot only 8-of-21 from the field. Shabazz Muhammad was the only other player to score in double digits for Minnesota, as he chipped in 11 off the bench. The Timberwolves move on to visit Los Angels, where they will take on the Lakers on Sunday.

The host Phoenix Suns stunned the Oklahoma City Thunder on Friday, winning, 120-99.

The Suns (23-57) did themselves no favors in terms of their lottery odds, as the win moved them back into a tie for second-worst record with the Los Angeles Lakers.  The resounding win did produce plenty of positives for the struggling team, though, as they saw 37 points from burgeoning star Devin Booker.  As a whole, Phoenix played a stellar game on the offensive end, shooting almost 52 percent from the field.  The Suns reached the free-throw line 31 times on the night, making 26 of their attempts.

OKC (45-34) saw a shocker, as the team had been rolling heading into Friday's game.  Superstar point guard Russell Westbrook was seen immediately heading to a practice court to put up shots after the loss, and given his performance, it may be hard to blame him.  The potential MVP had one of his worst outings of the season, shooting a dismal 6-of-25 from the field and turning the ball over eight times.  Though Westbrook finally officially secured a triple-double average for the season in the game, he failed to record a record-setting 42nd triple-double.  His poor shooting was also a large piece of OKC's offensive struggles on the night, as the team shot just 36 percent from the field.

OKC will visit Denver on Sunday, while Phoenix will host Dallas.

The host Los Angeles Lakers took down the Sacramento Kings on Friday, 98-94.

Los Angeles (24-55) will lose its draft pick to Philadelphia if it does not land in the top three.  However, the team is currently in the midst of an ill-timed three-game winning streak, its longest since November.   It was a relatively modest night for the Lakers on both ends on Friday. as the win was far from a dominant one.  However, four of the starting five managed to score in double figures, a positive sign for the young LA core.  Third-year forward Julius Randle had a team-high 25 points to go along with six rebounds.  The team as a whole shot 44 percent and forced 23 turnovers.  

The Kings (31-48) narrowly missed the win thanks to sloppy play on the offensive end.  Though the team shot over 50 percent and made eight three-pointers while holding LA to just four, turnovers ended up hurting Sacramento's chances.  The team's solid offensive effort included 27 team assists, but was offset by a whopping 23 turnovers on the night.  Rookie big man Skal Labissiere led the team on the offensive end, scoring a team-high 19 points along with two blocked shots on defense.  

On Sunday, Sacramento will host the Rockets while LA will host the Timberwolves.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 102-90, at Wells Fargo Center on Thursday evening.

The Bulls (39-40) checked into Thursday night sitting in the seventh seed in the Eastern Conference and armed with the good news that Dwyane Wade (elbow) would be returning to the lineup on Saturday night. However, they had to make sure and take care of business on the road against a Sixers (28-51) squad that had given many a team a difficult time. Chicago got off on the right foot with a 27-17 first-quarter lead and remained consistent throughout, while also playing stellar defense. The Bulls limited Philadelphia to success rates of 36.3 percent from the field and 21.2 percent from behind the arc, and they also won the rebounding battle by a 57-50 margin.

Nikola Mirotic led the way for the visitors with 22 points, eight rebounds, two assists and one block. Jimmy Butler followed with a 19-point, 10-rebound, 10-assist triple-double that also included a pair of steals. Jerian Grant contributed 15 points, eight boards, five assists and a pair of steals. Joffrey Lauvergne paced the second unit with 14 points, two rebounds, one assist and one steal. Bobby Portis was productive as a reserve as well with a 12-point, 11-rebound double-double in 21 minutes.

Timothe Luwawu-Cabarrot paced the Sixers with 18 points, three rebounds, three assists and two steals. Justin Anderson managed 17 points, four rebounds and one steal. Nik Stauskas followed with a bench-leading 13 points, four assists, three rebounds and one steal. Richaun Holmes supplied a 10-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included two assists, two steals and one block. Dario Saric mustered nine points, 10 boards, one assist, one steal and one block. T.J. McConnell filled out the stat sheet in typical fashion, producing nine points, eight assists, six rebounds and three steals. 

The Bulls next head to Brooklyn to tangle with the Nets on Saturday evening, while the Sixers remain home to tangle with the Milwaukee Bucks on Saturday night as well.

The Orlando Magic defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 115-107, at Amway Center on Thursday evening.

Both teams checked into Thursday's game having long been eliminated from playoff contention despite having the ability to put together some high scoring tallies on occasion. The Nets (19-60) had demonstrated as much on multiple occasions during their recent 6-4 stretch, while the Magic (28-51) had weapons in Elfrid Payton and Nikola Vucevic that matched up very well against Brooklyn's biggest weaknesses. All of those factors came into play Thursday, as both teams hit the 46-percent mark from the field and engaged in an entertaining see-saw battle. True to their recent level of play, the Nets wouldn't go away easily, mounting a fourth-quarter comeback that ultimately fell short. 

Jeremy Lin enjoyed a standout night, leading the way for the visitors with 32 points and supplementing them with five rebounds, three assists, two steals and one block. Caris LeVert followed with 20 points, which he supplemented with four boards and one assist. Brook Lopez had a quiet night, generating a modest 10 points, five rebounds and two assists over 31 minutes. Spencer Dinwiddie led the bench with 11 points, three rebounds, three assists, two steals and one block. Isaiah Whitehead and Justin Hamilton produced a pair of 10-point efforts off the bench as well. 

Elfrid Payton paced the Magic with a 22-point, 11-assist double-double that also included five rebounds, one steal and one block. Aaron Gordon registered 21 points, six rebounds, two assists and three steals. Jodie Meeks was next with 20 points and two rebounds. Nikola Vucevic tallied an 18-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included five assists and one steal. Mario Hezonja led the bench with 11 points, four rebounds, one assist and two blocks. 

The Nets head back home to tangle with the Chicago Bulls on Saturday night while the Magic remain home and await the Indiana Pacers for a Saturday evening showdown as well.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Milwaukee Bucks 104-89 Thursday at Bankers Life Fieldhouse. 

In Thursday's contest, the Pacers (39-40) never found themselves dominating at any one point. Rather, it was a steadily dominant 48 minutes for them, led by their superstar Paul George. George finished with a team-high 23 points on an efficient 9-of-14 shooting from the field to go along with 10 rebounds in 35 minutes. As a team, the Pacers saw six different players score in double figures in what was a wire-to-wire victory for Indiana. It wasn't the greatest shooting night, as the team shot 47.5 percent from the field and 32 percent from three, but it was enough to get it done thanks in large part to their stout defensive effort. 

The Bucks (40-39) didn't shoot horribly in the contest, as they actually hit 11 of their 24 (45.8 percent) three-point attempts. Rather, it was Indiana's ability to force turnovers that ultimately cost them the game, with Milwaukee choking the ball up 21 times, which was the same number of assists they had. The Bucks were led by Giannis Antetokounmpo, who had a great all-around game with 25 points, seven rebounds and six assists in 35 minutes, but only only two of his teammates managed to score in double figures as well, with Mirza Teletovic posting 15 points off the bench and Khris Middleton adding 10. The loss is the Bucks' third straight after they rattled off six wins in seven games. 

Up next, the Bucks will travel to Philadelphia on Saturday to take on the 76ers, while the Pacers will look to make it three straight wins when they head to Orlando on Saturday.

The Washington Wizards defeated the New York Knicks 106-103 Thursday at Madison Square Garden. 

Things looked to be going smoothly for the Wizards (48-31), as they managed to hold a comfortable lead throughout the first three quarters of Thursday's contest. However, a short Knicks' spurt in the final period ultimately tied the game at 97. In the end, some timely free throws and a final go-ahead three-pointer from Bradley Beal -- along with a missed three-pointer from Carmelo Anthony at the buzzer -- ultimately helped the Washington hold off the Knicks (30-49). Beal led the way for the Wizards, scoring a game-high 25 points in 36 minutes with John Wall not too far behind him, as the All-Star point guard notched 24 points on 9-of-15 shooting and eight assists in just 32 minutes. As a team, the Wizards were hot from behind the arc, hitting 14 of their 34 shots from long range (41.2 percent), and they ended up needing every last one of them. 

As for the Knicks, despite their season being all but over, they still managed to put together an inspiring performance in front of their home crowd. Anthony led the way with a team-high 23 points but on a fairly inefficient 7-of-19 shooting from the field. In the end, it was an all-around solid performance from New York, as six players in all managed to score in double figures, but they were just unable to hit all the shots they needed to hit during crunch time. Despite the loss, the Knicks are still team games ahead of both the Magic and 76ers for the second-worst record in the Eastern Conference. 

Up next, the Wizards will head home Saturday to take on the Heat, while the Knicks will head to Memphis on Friday to play the Grizzlies.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the Boston Celtics, 123-116, at Philips Arena on Thursday. 

These are two teams battling for playoff positioning and it was evident by the final scoreline. Despite Atlanta leading by 20 at times in the third quarter, Boston fought back and made it a close game. Rebounding was key for the Hawks, as they outrebounded the Celtics, 52-38. Atlanta also shot well, hitting 49 percent of their shots, while holding Boston to just 41 percent from the field. 

The Celtics (50-29) have now lost two-straight games, as the top-spot in the east is slowly slipping away. Isaiah Thomas did all he could for Boston, as he accumulated 35 points, five rebounds and four assists. Jae Crowder totaled 24 points and four rebounds. Avery Bradley amassed 17 points, four rebounds and two steals. Marcus Smart was huge off the bench, providing 18 points, four rebounds, seven assists, six steals and two blocks. On deck for the Celtics is a road matchup against the Charlotte Hornets on Saturday. 

The Hawks (40-38) needed this win after losing nine of their last 11 games and they came out hot to keep a hold on to the five-seed in the east. Paul Millsap was the player of the game, as he contributed 26 points, 12 rebounds, four assists and two steals off the bench. Tim Hardaway Jr finished with 23 points, five rebounds and five assists. Taurean Prince tallied 20 points, seven rebounds and four assists. Dennis Schroder collected 18 points, four rebounds and five assists. The next matchup for Atlanta is tough, as they have a road game versus the Cleveland Cavaliers on Friday.

The host Portland Trail Blazers took down the Minnesota Timberwolves on Thursday, 105-98.

Portland (39-40) is pushing for the playoffs and has recently taken control of the eight seed in the Western Conference.  Interestingly, it was sixth man Allen Crabbe who led the team's offensive push on Thursday.  Crabbe came off the bench and shot 8-of-12 en route to a team-high 25 points to go along with five rebounds and three assists.  Thanks in large part to Crabbe, Portland enjoyed a major advantage in bench scoring.  The Blazers held a 37-13 edge in points off the bench.  Point guard Damian Lillard also enjoyed a stellar game, scoring 22 points to go along with nine rebounds and eight assists.  

Minnesota (31-47) has been eliminated from playoff contention but still put up a strong fight on Thursday night.  It was a particularly great night for the young dynamic duo of Andrew Wiggins and Karl-Anthony Towns.  Wiggins led the game with 36 points on 14-of-27 shooting to go along with eight rebounds.
