Towns, meanwhile, had a massive double-double, recording 24 points, 16 rebounds, a block and a steal.  The rest of the team, however, had some struggles, as they shot just 43 percent from the field as a unit and saw only 13 points off the bench.  

The Timberwolves will visit Utah on Friday, while Portland will host the Jazz on Saturday.

The Miami Heat defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 112-99, at Spectrum Center on Wednesday night. 

The Heat (38-40) came into Wednesday knowing that a win would vault them back to the coveted eighth seed in the Eastern Conference. Miami had a tall order in front of them, however, as the Hornets (36-43) owned a winning record at home and were fighting for that eighth spot in their own right, although from a less advantageous position than their visitors. As it turned out, it was the Heat that looked considerably more postseason-worthy, utilizing a big third quarter to pull away from the double-digit road win. The duo of Goran Dragic and James Johnson were spectacular while combining for 59 points, and Hassan Whiteside posted a huge double-double down low on a night in which Miami won the rebounding battle by a 40-36 margin. 

Dragic led the way with a game-high 33 points, which he supplemented with four assists, one rebound and two steals. Johnson tallied 26 points, four boards, three assists and two steals. Josh Richardson was next with 19 points, six rebounds, five assists and one block. Whiteside managed a 13-point, 20-rebound double-double that also included three blocks and one steal. Tyler Johnson led the way for the bench with 12 points, three assists and two rebounds.

Nicolas Batum set the pace for Charlotte, supplying 24 points, seven assists, three rebounds, one steal and one block. Kemba Walker registered 18 points, five assists and two rebounds. Marvin Williams pitched in with a 15-point, 12-rebound double-double. Cody Zeller and Michael Kidd-Gilchrist each submitted eight-point efforts, while Frank Kaminsky led the second unit with 13 points, one rebound and one assist.

The Heat next head to Toronto for a Friday night showdown with the Raptors, while the Hornets remain home to tangle with the Boston Celtics on Saturday evening.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the host Detroit Pistons, 105-102, at Palace of Auburn Hills on Wednesday. 

This game was full of swings, as Toronto made a huge comeback to put Detroit's playoff hopes in jeopardy. In fact, the Raptors trailed by 12 headed into the fourth quarter, but proceeded to outscore the Pistons, 37-22, in the fourth quarter to comeback and win. Free-throw shooting was a huge factor, as Detroit went just 11-of-18 from the charity stripe, while Toronto hit 13-of-15. The Raptors also dominated the assist-to-turnover ratio, recording seven more assists than Detroit, while committing three less turnovers. 

The Raptors (48-31) got Kyle Lowry back from a wrist injury after a two-month absence and his presence in this comeback shows how important he is to this team. Lowry led Toronto, as he tallied 27 points, five rebounds, 10 assists and two steals. Jonas Valanciunas finished second on the team, as he totaled 19 points and five rebounds on 9-of-11 shooting. DeMar DeRozan went just 5-of-17 from the field, but still finished with 12 points, four rebounds and 10 assists. Cory Joseph played well off the bench, as he provided 15 points, five rebounds and two steals. On deck for the Raptors is a home matchup versus the Miami Heat on Friday. 

The Pistons (35-43) are fighting for a playoff berth and blown leads like this are devastating for that pursuit. Ish Smith led the starters, as he accumulated 16 points, four rebounds and six assists. Tobias Harris matched those 16 points to lead the bench. Andre Drummond recorded a double-double, totaling 11 points and 14 rebounds. Detroit will look to stay alive on Friday in a road matchup against the Houston Rockets.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 103-100, at FedEx Forum on Wednesday night.

All eyes were on Russell Westbrook even more so than usual, as he entered Wednesday's contest just one triple-double short of breaking Oscar Robertson's NBA record for most in a season. However, the game had larger implications, as the Thunder (45-33) were also trying to stave off the Grizzlies (42-37) for the sixth seed in the Western Conference. As expected, the high-stakes game was a tightly-contested one, with Memphis closing an early 34-27 first-quarter deficit. Fittingly, the outcome came down to the final seconds, with Westbrook's key 25-foot three-pointer with 14 seconds remaining providing Oklahoma City with a 101-97 cushion. Andrew Harrison's own trey with under a second left closed the gap to one, but Westbrook drained a pair of free throws for the final margin of victory. 

As customary, the Thunder's stat sheet was decidedly top-heavy. Westbrook led the way while falling just short of Robertson's record, as he posted 45 points, 10 assists, nine rebounds and five steals. Victor Oladipo filled his usual role as a distant second option, pouring in 15 points and adding five assists, three rebounds, one steal and one block. Steven Adams mustered a modest five points but hauled in 10 rebounds and added an assist and a block. Taj Gibson pitched in with eight points, seven rebounds and one steal, while Doug McDermott and Enes Kanter led the bench with a pair of 10-point efforts.

The Grizzlies were led by Marc Gasol, who tallied 23 points, five rebounds, five assists, four blocks and two steals. Zach Randolph followed with a bench-leading 20 points, which he supplemented with nine rebounds, one assist and one steal. Tony Allen contributed 14 points, seven boards, four assists and two steals. Harrison, starting for the injured Mike Conley (eye), registered 12 points, three rebounds and three assists. Vince Carter provided 10 points, two rebounds and two assists. 

The Thunder travel to Phoenix to take on the Suns on Friday night, while the Grizzlies are home against the Knicks on Friday evening as well.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Denver Nuggets, 110-104, at Toyota Center on Wednesday. 

In a game with major playoff implications, both these teams left it all on the floor. Despite there being just five ties and five lead changes in total, the game was within a six-point margin for the final 20 minutes. Three-point shooting killed the Nuggets, as they went 7-of-38 from long range, while the Rockets hit 10-of-34. Houston took care of the defensive rebounding, as they won that battle, 45-39. Despite Denver winning the turnover differential for the game, they committed six of their 12 turnovers in the fourth quarter. 

The Nuggets (37-41) came into this game just one game out of the eight-seed in the West, as this loss is devastating for that goal. Danilo Gallinari led Denver, as he tallied 23 points, five rebounds and three assists. Nikola Jokic flirted with a triple-double, accumulating 12 points, 19 rebounds, nine assists and five steals. Gary Harris finished with 17 points, while Wilson Chandler dropped 16 points and five rebounds off the bench. On deck for Denver is a home matchup against the New Orleans Pelicans on Friday. 

The Rockets (53-25) are secure in the three-seed in the West, but they're still playing hard night after night. James Harden led the way, as he collected 31 points, seven rebounds, 10 assists and three blocks. Clint Capela recorded a double-double, totaling 15 points and 11 rebounds. Patrick Beverley finished with nine points, 11 rebounds and two steals. Trevor Ariza amassed 15 points and 10 rebounds. Nene Hilario was a nice spark off the bench, providing 16 points, four rebounds and two assists on 7-of-8 shooting. Houston's next game will be on Friday against the Detroit Pistons.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the Boston Celtics, 114-91, Wednesday at TD Garden. 

The Cavaliers (51-27) came into Wednesday's contest with revenge on their minds, and following a low-scoring, tightly contested first quarter that saw the Celtics (50-28) take a one-point lead, the motivation kicked in; at least for LeBron James it did. James launched a 22-4 run to open up the second quarter and he and his teammates never looked back, as Boston was unable to get much closer than that throughout the remainder of Wednesday's game. James finished with a game-high 36 points, 10 rebounds and six assists in 39 minutes as his team avenged their last-second loss at Boston earlier in the season. Each of the other four Cleveland starters joined James in reaching double figures in the scoring column, but the story of the game was their defense. 

The Cavaliers' defensive effort was their best in a long time, as 91 points is the fewest they've given up since March 16 against the Jazz. The Celtics managed to shoot just 40.7 percent from the field, 21.2 percent from behind the arc, and to make matters even worse, 62 percent from the free throw line. It was the first time in nine games that Boston failed to score at least 100 points and their lowest point total since they scored 88 against the Warriors on Nov. 18. Isaiah Thomas still managed to lead the way with a team-high 26 points to go along with six assists and four rebounds, but no other Celtic scored more than 13 points in the loss. 

The win for Cleveland moves them one game ahead of the Celtics for first place in the Eastern Conference standings with just four games remaining for each team.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the San Antonio Spurs, 102-95, Wednesday at AT&T Center. 

On a night where Spurs (60-18) head coach Gregg Popovich decided to rest his key players for the majority of the game, the Lakers (23-55) decided to take advantage, and they wasted no time doing so. After one quarter, Los Angeles had opened up their lead to 17 points, and that lead eventually grew to as much as 26 in the first half. San Antonio, even without their star players playing heavy minutes on a back-to-back, managed to trim the lead and get it to a tie early in the fourth quarter. 

Unfortunately for them, they never could get over the hump thanks in large part to Tyler Ennis, who got the spot start at point guard with D'Angelo Russell out with a knee injury. Ennis led the way for the Lakers with a game-high 19 points on 8-of-14 shooting from the field and six assists in 39 minutes. Jordan Clarkson wasn't too far behind with 17 points, and in total, Los Angeles had five players score in double figures. In the end, the Lakers allowed their hot shooting to carry them to victory, as they hit 48.8 percent of their field goal attempts and 50 percent from behind the arc. 

As for the Spurs, it was essentially a night off for them, as Kawhi Leonard, Tony Parker, LaMarcus Aldridge and Pau Gasol all played 18 minutes or less. Somehow, Tony Parker managed to tie for the team-lead in points Wednesday night, as he scored 14 points on 7-of-11 shooting in just 16 minutes, with Davis Bertans matching him with 14 points of his own off the bench. In all, four Spurs did manage to hit double-digit scoring totals, but they ended up just hitting 43.8 percent of their field goal attempts in the losing effort. 

Up next, San Antonio will travel to Dallas on Thursday to take on the Mavericks, while the Lakers will head home Friday to play the Kings.

Despite a close game down the stretch, the visiting Golden State Warriors managed to beat the Phoenix Suns on Wednesday, 120-111.

Golden State (65-14) clinched the league's best record for the third straight season with the win.  The team also extended its league-best win streak to 13 games.  It was almost inevitable that the Warriors would walk away with the win after they started the game with a 40-18 first quarter advantage.  Despite that, however, Phoenix was able to bring the game back to a nail-biter by the late fourth quarter.  Still, it was tough for the Suns to do anything to stop reigning MVP Steph Curry.  Curry scored a team-high 42 points while dishing out 11 assists.  The other "Splash Brother," Klay Thompson, added 22 points.  On the whole, the Dubs shot 50 percent on the night and made 13 three-pointers.  

Phoenix (22-57) dropped its 13th consecutive game and continues to sit at the bottom of the Western Conference.  The Suns shot only 41 percent on the night on Wednesday, but kept things close with Golden State thanks to strong rebounding.  Phoenix held a 55-40 advantage on the boards and pulled down a whopping 20 offensive rebounds.  At the heart of the rebounding effort was young big man Alan Williams, who had a 16-point, 17-rebound double-double in just 25 minutes of play.

On Friday, Phoenix will host OKC, while Golden State will host the Pelicans on Saturday.

The host Los Angeles Clippers took down the Dallas Mavericks on Wednesday, 112-101.

The Clippers (48-31) have now won four straight and are seeing their "Big Three" come together as the end of the season draws near.  On Wednesday, All-Star forward Blake Griffin scored 32 points while dishing out six assists, and superstar point guard Chris Paul had a 22-point, 11-assist double-double.  Center DeAndre Jordan, meanwhile, stole the show with a whopping 20 rebounds and 11 points on 4-of-5 shooting.  The team saw stellar 51 percent shooting from the field and drained 12 three-pointers on the night.

Dallas (32-46) is now left hoping for better lottery position as the team has been eliminated from playoff contention.  Shooting guard Seth Curry sat out of action again due to injury, leaving a depleted Mavs team to take on the scorching-hot Clippers.  Five players ended up scoring in double digits for the team, but the team-high proved to be just 15.  As a whole, Dallas shot only 44 percent from the field.  They also struggled with turnovers, committing 16 on the night.  

The Mavericks will host the Spurs on Friday, while the Clippers will visit the Spurs on Saturday.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 118-114, at Wells Fargo Center on Tuesday night.

The Sixers (28-50) checked into Tuesday having lost three straight games and hoping that a return to their home court would prove to be the cure for what ailed them. On paper, they appeared to have the right matchup to capitalize on, as the Nets (19-59), although improved as of late, were still sporting a 6-31 road record at the start of the night. Nothing could have prepared Philadelphia for the onslaught they were subjected to, as Brooklyn tied a franchise record with 81 first-half points. They shot 70 percent and made 12-of-17 three-pointers during the first two quarters and saw eight players hit double digits in the scoring column. Four of those efforts came from the second unit, which collectively tallied a whopping 78 points on the night. Overall, Brooklyn posted a jaw-dropping 64 percent success rate from the field, along with an excellent 51.6 percent figure from three-point range.

Brook Lopez and Jeremy Lin led the Nets with matching 16-point efforts, with the former adding four rebounds, one assist and three blocks and the latter providing seven assists, five boards and two steals. Archie Goodwin and K.J. McDaniels followed with 14-point contributions off the bench. Goodwin added two rebounds, two assists and a steal, while McDaniels collected two rebounds and one assist. Sean Kilpatrick and Spencer Dinwiddie had 13 points apiece, along with three rebounds, three assists and a steal for Kilpatrick and seven assists, two rebounds and two steals for Dinwiddie. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson (12 points, three rebounds and two assists) and Randy Foye (12 points, three boards, two assists and two steals) rounded out the double-digit scoring.

The Sixers were led by promising rookie Timothe Luwawu-Cabarrot, who totaled 19 points, three rebounds, three assists and three steals. Shawn Long was next with a bench-leading 18 points, which he supplemented with six boards and two assists. Richaun Holmes totaled 16 points, six rebounds, four assists, three blocks and one steal. Justin Anderson contributed 13 points, three assists and two rebounds. T.J. McConnell matched Anderson's point total and complemented it with seven assists, two rebounds, one steal and one block. Dario Saric had a modest night with 10 points, three rebounds, two assists and a steal. Alex Poythress matched Saric's point total off the bench.

The Nets next head to Orlando to take on the Magic on Thursday evening while the Sixers are home against the Chicago Bulls that same night.

The Washington Wizards defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 118-111, at Verizon Center on Tuesday.

Charlotte needed to win this game to keep their playoff hopes alive, but this loss may be the nail in their coffin. The third quarter is what really changed the result, with Washington turning a 12-point deficit into a six-point lead. Both teams were efficient on offense, as they both shot 51 percent from the field. The Wizards dominated from long distance though, hitting 17-of-34 from three-point range, while Charlotte went just 12-of-34. Washington also dominated the assist-to-turnover ratio, recording 10 more assists than the Hornets, while committing two less turnovers. 

The Hornets (36-42) are trying to get back to the eight-seed in the East, but this loss is devastating for pursuit. Kemba Walker did all he could though, as he led them with 37 points, five rebounds, four assists and two steals. Marco Belinelli finished second on the team, as he provided 16 points, three rebounds and two assists off the bench. Nicolas Batum accrued 13 points and eight assists. Cody Zeller totaled 10 points and 10 rebounds en route to a double-double. On deck for the Hornets is a home matchup versus the Miami Heat on Wednesday. 

The Wizards (49-31) are now tied with the Toronto Raptors for the three-seed in the East, as they continue their amazing season. John Wall led them once again, as he collected 23 points, 13 assists and six steals. Bradley Beal amassed 19 points, two rebounds, four assists and three steals. Jason Smith and Kelly Oubre Jr. were huge off the bench, as they combined for 32 points, 10 rebounds and three assists. Washington's next game is on Thursday against the New York Knicks.

The Cleveland Cavaliers toppled the Orlando Magic, 122-102, at Quicken Loans Arena on Tuesday evening.

The Cavaliers (50-27) are trying to stack up as many wins as possible, in an effort to both keep up with the Boston Celtics in the Eastern Conference and to restore some of the confidence they lost during a recent extended skid. However, matters weren't looking too promising in the first half against the inferior Magic (27-51) on Tuesday, as Orlando actually entered halftime with a 55-53 lead. Cleveland came out of the locker room a new team, though, taking the third period by a score of 43-20. That gave them the cushion necessary to ride to a relatively comfortable victory, one that saw them shoot 53.7 and 50 percent from the field and three-point range, respectively.

Evan Fournier led the way for Orlando with 21 points, which he supplemented with one assist and two steals. Mario Hezonja followed with a bench-leading 13 points, which he supplemented with two rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Elfrid Payton, Terrence Ross and Aaron Gordon were next with a trio of 12-point efforts. Payton added six assists and four rebounds, Ross provided three assists, one rebound and two steals and Gordon tallied five rebounds in addition to his scoring. Nikola Vucevic compiled a modest six points but also hauled in 10 rebounds, dished out two assists, and recorded a steal and a block. Jodie Meeks was productive as a reserve as well with 11 points, six boards, three assists and two steals.

Kevin Love paced Cleveland with 28 points, 11 rebounds, two assists, two steals and one block. Kyrie Irving supplied 24 points, eight assists, four rebounds and one steal. J.R. Smith poured in 19 points and added five rebounds and three assists. LeBron James contributed an 18-point, 11-rebound, 11-assist triple-double that also included two steals and one block. Kyle Korver led the bench with 11 points, one rebound and one assist.

The Magic head back home to take on the Brooklyn Nets on Thursday night while the Cavs head to Beantown for a pivotal showdown against the Celtics on Wednesday evening.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Toronto Raptors, 108-90, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Tuesday. 

Indiana needed this game to keep playoff hopes alive and they rode a furious comeback to increase their odds. In fact, after trailing by 11 at the half, the Pacers outscored the Raptors, 68-39, in the second half to comeback and win by 18. The big advantage for Indiana was their shooting, as they dominated the three-point shooting, while going a perfect 18-of-18 from the free-throw line. The Pacers ended up shooting 12-of-25 from long distance, while Toronto went just 5-of-23. 

The Raptors (47-31) are now tied with the Washington Wizards for the three-seed in the East, as this loss could cause complications for playoff positioning. DeMar DeRozan led the way for Toronto, as he tallied 27 points, three rebounds, two assists and three steals. Jonas Valanciunas recorded a double-double, totaling 10 points and 10 rebounds. Serge Ibaka went just 3-of-13 from the field to finish with eight points and 10 rebounds. Toronto's next game will be on Wednesday in a road matchup versus the Detroit Pistons. 

The Pacers (38-40) desperately needed this win with their playoff hopes slimming and this win showed some serious resiliency. Paul George scored a game-high 35 points to add to his 10 rebounds, three assists and two steals. Thaddeus Young accrued 15 points, 11 rebounds and two steals. Jeff Teague collected 20 points and six assists. Lance Stephenson came off the bench to provide 12 points, two rebounds and three assists in his return to Indy. On deck for the Pacers is a home matchup against the Milwaukee Bucks on Thursday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the New Orleans Pelicans, 134-131, at Smoothie King Center on Tuesday evening.

Both the Nuggets (37-40) and Pelicans (33-45) came in as Western Conference playoff hopefuls striving to keep postseason hopes alive. However, New Orleans faced elimination with a loss, which gave them an extra dose of motivation while playing in front of their home crowd. The game unfolded exactly as one with as high a stakes should, with both teams seemingly matching each other point-for-point through the majority of four quarters. In the end, it came down to some crucial fourth-quarter sequences, including a pair of late threes from DeMarcus Cousins, with the second tying the game at 131 with 30.5 seconds remaining. However, Jrue Holiday turned the ball over twice in the last minute, with both miscues leading to crucial Nuggets free throws. Holiday had a chance for redemption as time expired, but his 27-foot three-point attempt couldn't find the net. As expected in such a high-scoring affair, both teams were excellent from the field, with New Orleans posting a 51.0 percent success rate and Denver countering with a 53.5 percent figure. 

Danilo Gallinari led the way for Denver with 28 points, five rebounds and three assists. Gary Harris filled out the stat sheet with 23 points, eight rebounds, five assists and two steals. Nikola Jokic managed a 21-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included four assists. Wilson Chandler followed with a bench-leading 18 points, which he supplemented with seven boards and two assists. Jamal Murray tallied 16 points, five rebounds, five assists and one steal. Emmanuel Mudiay (15 points, seven assists) and Mason Plumlee (13 points, 11 boards, three assists and a block) were productive as reserves as well.

Anthony Davis paced the Pelicans with 41 points, five rebounds, four blocks and one steal. Cousins contributed a near triple-double of 30 points, 14 rebounds, nine assists, two blocks and one steal. Despite the unfortunate turn of events in the final seconds, Holiday turned in an impressive game, posting an 18-point 13-assist double-double that also included four rebounds, a steal and a block. Solomon Hill compiled 15 points, four rebounds, one block and one steal. E'Twaun Moore led the second unit with 13 points, three rebounds, three assists and one block.

The Nuggets next travel to the Lone Star State to tangle with the Houston Rockets on Wednesday evening, while the Pelicans head to the Mile High City for a rematch with Denver on Friday night.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Milwaukee Bucks, 110-79, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Tuesday. 

This game was expected to be close, but Oklahoma City had other ideas. In fact, the Thunder led by 24 at half and 30 headed into a non-competitive fourth quarter. Rebounding was huge for Oklahoma City, as they won that battle, 53-38. They also dominated the shooting, hitting 48 percent of their shots, while holding Milwaukee to just 36 percent from the field. A 54-40 scoring in the paint differential was a huge factor for the Thunder as well. All the talk will be around Russell Westbrook though, as he tied Oscar Robertsonl's record for the most triple-doubles in a season, as Westbrook picked up his 41st on the year in this win. 

The Bucks (40-38) are fending off numerous teams for the final few playoff spots in the East and non-competitive losses like this certainty can't help that pursuit. Giannis Antetokounmpo tallied 11 points, 10 rebounds, four assists and three blocks. Michael Beasley led the team in scoring, as he dropped 14 points off the bench. On deck for Milwaukee is a road matchup with the Indiana Pacers on Thursday. 

The Thunder (44-33) have rode Westbrook all season long and he recorded his 41st triple-double in just three quarters of action in this blowout victory. Westbrook finished the game with 12 points, 13 rebounds and 13 assists. Enes Kanter was huge off the bench, as he provided 17 points, five rebounds and two steals. Andre Roberson had a nice all-around game, collecting four points, five rebounds, four assists, three steals and three blocks. Westbrook will look to set that record on Wednesday, when the Thunder travel to face the Memphis Grizzlies for their next game.

The New York Knicks defeated the Chicago Bulls, 100-91, Tuesday at Madison Square Garden. 

Tuesday's contest ended up being a major letdown for the Bulls (38-40) but an impressive win for the struggling Knicks (30-48) who were without both Kristaps Porzingis (back) and Derrick Rose (knee). They did, however, get Carmelo Anthony back after their star missed the previous two games with his own back problems, and he managed to lead the team offensively with a team-high 23 points and seven rebounds in 37 minutes in a game that New York led convincingly from start to finish. As a team, it wasn't the most impressive offensive performance from the Knicks, as they shot just 26 percent from behind the arc and 62.5 percent from the free throw line, but in the end, five different players managing to score in double figures was enough to get the job done. 

As for Chicago, Tuesday's loss was simply one they couldn't afford, as while they are still technically in the playoffs in the East, they are now tied with the Pacers and just a half-game ahead of the Heat, who are now barely on the outside looking in.  Jimmy Butler lead the way for the Bulls with a game-high 26 points, while Nikola Mirotic added 21 points of his own, but they weren't fortunate enough to get much help offensively, as four different Chicago players who played at least 14 minutes failed to score more than five points. As a team, they shot just 38.1 percent from the field and 22.2 percent from behind the arc. 

Up next, the Bulls will look to stay alive in the playoff chase Thursday against the 76ers, while the Knicks will remain home Thursday and play the Wizards.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 95-89, in overtime Tuesday at AT&T Center. 

It was a low-scoring, back-and-forth affair Tuesday night, which kept the game relatively close throughout the the original 48 minutes of the contest. With the Spurs (60-17) looking to pull away with just over three minutes left in the fourth quarter, the Grizzlies (42-36) managed to go on a quick 8-0 spurt that put them up by one point with a minute and a half remaining. For the final minute of Tuesday's game, the teams went on to trade baskets, with three made buckets coming in the last four seconds and putting the game into overtime. From there, it was all Spurs, who dominated on the defensive end throughout the extra period to earn the victory. 

Kawhi Leonard put together yet another tremendous performance for San Antonio, finishing with a game-high 32 points to go along with 12 rebounds and four assists in 40 minutes. LaMarcus Aldridge added 15 points and six rebounds of his own in 41 minutes, while Pau Gasol came off the bench to notch a double-double himself, posting 12 points and 11 boards in 31 minutes as a reserve. As a team, the Spurs were absolutely on fire from downtown, shooting 11-of-21 (52.4 percent) from behind the arc. 

As for the Grizzlies, they battled hard despite dealing with multiple injuries to their star players, as Mike Conley was forced to leave injury after an eye injury, while Marc Gasol was limited with a foot injury and held out of the overtime period as a result. Conley still managed to lead the team in scoring with 19 points to go along with six assists in 33 minutes, but the biggest performance came off the bench from Zach Randolph, who finished with a double-double of 18 points and 16 rebounds in 35 minutes as a reserve. Overall, however, it was a struggle offensively for Memphis on Tuesday night, as they managed to hit just 39.3 percent of their shots from the field.

The Utah Jazz defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 106-87, Tuesday at Vivint Smart Home Arena.

The Jazz started the game on a quick 11-0 run, and while the Trail Blazers ultimately fought back hard to take a 31-30 lead in the second quarter, that lead ended up lasting just 15 seconds and it would be the last lead they would have all game. From that point on, Utah started to roll once again and ultimately walked off their home floor with a convincing 19-point victory. Gordon Hayward lead the way for the Jazz with a game-high 30 points on 12-of-20 shooting from the field, while Rudy Gobert shot a perfect 6-of-6 from the field and 8-of-10 from the charity stripe in route to recording 20 points to go along with 11 rebounds and three blocks. In the end, six different Utah players managed to score in double figures as the team shot the lights out Tuesday night. As a team, the Jazz hit 53.4 percent of their field goals overall and an even more impressive 56.5 percent of their threes in the victory. 

As for Portland, they have now dropped two straight games after rattling off six straight wins and now find themselves just a half-game ahead of the Nuggets for the eighth and final playoff spot in the Western Conference. C.J. McCollum had a strong outing, shooting 11-of-22 from the field en route to scoring a team-high 25 points, but it ended up being a night to forget for his sidekick Damian Lillard. Lillard shot an abysmal 5-of-20 from the field en route to scoring just 16 points in 34 minutes, and beyond the backcourt, only one other Trail Blazer managed to score in double figures, with Al-Farouq Aminu scoring a light 11 points in 31 minutes. As a team, Portland accumulated just 10 total assists and shot a poor 39.8 percent from the field.

The host Golden State Warriors took down the Minnesota Timberwolves on Tuesday, 121-107.

Golden State (64-14) continues to roll, winning its 12th straight game against the Wolves.  On Tuesday, it was shooting guard Klay Thompson who led the team to victory, scoring 41 points on the night while shooting 13-of-24 and pouring in seven three-pointers.  As a team, the Warriors saw an impressive offensive night, shooting over 52 percent and hitting a superb 14 three-pointers.  The Dubs also dished out a massive 33 assists, with nine coming from two-time reigning MVP Steph Curry.

Minnesota (31-46) kept with the Warriors in the first half but fell victim to yet another dominant Warriors third quarter.  It was a typically dominant night for the young up-and-comers of Minnesota, as Karl-Anthony Towns and Andrew Wiggins both scored over 20 points.  Wiggins finished with 24 points, tying bench forward Shabazz Muhammad for the team lead.  Muhammad also pulled down 11 rebounds on the night.  It was a nice night for the whole team on the boards, as they out-rebounded Golden State 50-40 on the game.  

The Warriors will visit Phoenix on Wednesday, while the Timberwolves will visit Portland on Thursday.

The host Sacramento Kings took down the Dallas Mavericks on Tuesday, 98-87.

Sacramento (31-47) blew by the Mavericks at the end of the game after a tied game leading up to the mid-fourth quarter.  Play was fairly strong on the offensive end, as the Kings shot 45 percent from the field and sunk 12 three-pointers.  The leader of the Kings' scoring charge was bench guard Ben McLemore, who shot 8-of-13 for 22 points on the night.  They also dominated on the boards, out-rebounding the Mavericks by a margin of 50-39.  

Dallas (32-45) stayed in the game until roughly seven minutes remained, but finished out the game rolling out a lineup of almost entirely bench players.  The Kings managed to take a double-digit lead on the Mavericks as the fourth quarter began to wane.  Offense proved to be a major issue for the Mavs, as the team shot just 40 percent on the night.  Only three players scored in double figures and saw forward Nicolas Brussino lead the team with just 13 points.  The Mavericks also struggled to reach the free-throw line, attempting only 14 free-throws on the night.  

The Mavericks will visit the Los Angeles Clippers on Wednesday, while the Kings will visit the Lakers on Friday.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 110-109, at Target Center on Monday night.

Two offensively-potent squads engaged in the type of game that would be expected of them, with each unit seemingly taking turns racking up points on each other throughout the first three periods. Matters tightened up in the fourth, a quarter which the Timberwolves (31-45) had entered holding a slim 86-83 lead. The Trail Blazers (38-39) got within one with an Al-Farouq Aminu basket with 30 seconds remaining but could get no closer, with Damian Lillard missing a would-be game-winning 17-footer as time expired that sent Minnesota home victors. The Timberwolves shot a stellar 49.4 percent from the field while winning the rebounding battle by a 43-35 margin.

Lillard led the way with 25 points, six assists, four rebounds and two steals. Aminu followed with a bench-leading 20 points, which he supplemented with seven boards, five assists and three blocks. Maurice Harkless and C.J. McCollum followed with matching 17-point efforts, with the former adding eight rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block and the latter providing five rebounds, four assists, one steal and one block. Noah Vonleh tallied 12 points, four boards, two steals and two blocks and Allen Crabbe matched his scoring total off the bench while also registering two assists, one rebound and one steal. 

Karl-Anthony Towns paced the Timberwolves with 34 points and 12 boards. Andrew Wiggins followed with 29 points and three rebounds. Brandon Rush compiled 12 points, seven rebounds, three assists, two blocks and one steal. Ricky Rubio posted an 11-point, 16-assist double-double that also included seven rebounds and one block. Gorgui Dieng submitted a full stat line of eight points, eight rebounds, three assists and two blocks. Shabazz Muhammad led the second unit with 11 points and one rebound.

The Trail Blazers head to Utah for a Tuesday night showdown with the Jazz while the Timberwolves face off with the Golden  State Warriors on Tuesday night as well.

The Boston Celtics defeated the New York Knicks, 110-94, at Madison Square Garden on Sunday afternoon.

The Knicks (29-48) came into Sunday's matchup knowing that they'd once again be playing without some of their most potent offensive pieces in Carmelo Anthony (back) and Derrick Rose (knee). That naturally led to low expectations against a Celtics (50-27) squad that was gunning for their 50th win of the season and trying to keep hold of the top spot in the Eastern Conference. The game played out more or less as expected, as Boston utilized a balanced offensive effort and a 34-23 first quarter to cruise to a relatively comfortable victory. The Celtics enjoyed a stellar shooting performance (55.6 percent) and played excellent defense, allowing them to overcome a rather sloppy 17 turnovers. 

Isaiah Thomas led the way for the visitors with 19 points, six assists, two rebounds and one steal. Jaylen Brown posted 16 points, two boards and one assist. Al Horford followed with 14 points, seven rebounds and one assist. Marcus Smart matched Horford's scoring total off the bench and added five assists, two rebounds and one steal. Kelly Olynyk and Terry Rozier were productive as reserves as well with 12-point efforts. Amir Johnson contributed nine points and three rebounds and Jae Crowder tallied eight points, five boards and one steal before exiting after 28 minutes with an elbow injury. 

The Knicks were paced by Courtney Lee, who pitched in 16 points, five assists, three rebounds and one steal. Kristaps Porzingis was next with 14 points, one rebound and one steal. Willy Hernangomez supplied 12 points, three rebounds, three assists and two steals. Mindaugas Kuzminskas and Kyle O'Quinn led the second unit with a pair of 11-point efforts, with the former adding one rebound and one assist and the latter registering nine boards and two blocks. Chasson Randle poured in 10 points and added three assists, two rebounds and one steal over 22 minutes as a reserve.

The Celtics head back home for a pivotal showdown with the Cleveland Cavaliers on Wednesday evening, while the Knicks are off until Tuesday night when the face the Chicago Bulls on Tuesday night at home as well.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the Oklahoma City Thunder, 113-101, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Sunday afternoon.

There is naturally no actual downside to having Russell Westbrook on your squad, but his mere presence can often serve to elevate the game of the opposing point guard. The motivation of playing against the best in the league seemed to give Kemba Walker, an All-Star in his own right, a bit of an extra step Sunday, as he led the Hornets (36-41) to a crucial upset road victory with 29 points, four assists, three rebounds and four steals. Walker was an outstanding 10-of-20 from the field overall and 6-of-12 from three-point range. Still in the hunt for a postseason berth, Charlotte came out strong in the first and third quarters, outscoring the Thunder (43-33) by a combined 56-38 margin during those periods. Although Westbrook did contribute yet another triple-double with 40 points, 13 rebounds, 10 assists and three steals, the Hornets played solid defense overall, causing 24 turnovers.

Frank Kaminsky followed Walker with a bench-leading 18 points, which he supplemented with two rebounds, two steals and one block. Michael Kidd-Gilchrist followed with 16 points, six boards, one assist and two steals. Jeremy Lamb was productive as a reserve as well with 13 points, three boards and one steal. Cody Zeller contributed 11 points, four rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. Nicolas Batum filled out the stat sheet with nine points, eight assists, seven rebounds and three steals. 

Victor Oladipo posted 19 points, six assists, three rebounds and one steal. Andre Roberson managed 12 points, six rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Enes Kanter led the bench with nine points and one rebound, while Jerami Grant was right behind him with eight points, three rebounds, one assist and one block.

The Hornets continue their quest for the playoffs with a trip to the Nation's Capital to tangle with the Wizards on Tuesday evening, while the Thunder face off with the Milwaukee Bucks at home on Tuesday night as well.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 108-103, at Staples Center on Sunday afternoon.

Despite the fact that they were playing without frontcourt starters Marc Gasol and JaMychal Green, the Grizzlies (42-35) had to be feeling fairly confident about their chances against a Lakers (22-55) squad that had dropped 10 of their last 11 games. However, Sunday happened to be one of those afternoons when Los Angeles came to play, as they forged a 50-49 halftime lead and hung close throughout the second half. A 29-23 advantage in the fourth quarter led to the victory, one that saw the Lakers shoot a solid 47.1 percent from the field and six players hit double digits in the scoring column. 

Mike Conley and Troy Daniels paced the Grizzlies with matching 20-point efforts, with the former adding 12 assists, three rebounds, one steal and one block and the latter registering three assists, two rebounds and one steal to lead the bench. Brandan Wright continued to start for Gasol and generated 16 points, three rebounds, two assists and one block. James Ennis III drew a spot start with Vince Carter resting and managed 14 points, eight boards, four assists, one steal and one block. Tony Allen contributed a near double-double with 13 points, nine boards, three assists, two steals and one block. Zach Randolph matched Allen's scoring while leading the bench and added six rebounds, one assist and one steal. 

D'Angelo Russell led the way for the home team with 28 points, six rebounds and five assists. Julius Randle produced an 18-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included one steal and one block. Brandon Ingram contributed 13 points, three rebounds, one assist and one steal. Larry Nance, Jr. drew another start and tallied 12 points, 14 boards, one assist, three steals and one block. Thomas Robinson enjoyed his third consecutive solid game, posting a 12-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included one assist and two steals and led the second unit. Tyler Ennis was productive off the bench as well with 11 points, two boards, one assist and one steal.

The Grizzlies next head to San Antonio to battle the Spurs on Tuesday evening, while the Lakers follow the Grizzlies into Texas and face off with the Spurs on Wednesday night.

The Dallas Mavericks prevailed over the Milwaukee Bucks, 109-105, Sunday afternoon at BMO Harris Bradley Center.

The Mavericks (32-44) were officially eliminated from the playoffs by virtue of Portland's victory over Phoenix on Saturday night, but they displayed plenty of heart while upsetting the postseason-bound Bucks (40-37), who were looking to improve their playoff positioning. Only four Dallas players managed double-digit scoring, but the Mavs shot 52.1 percent from the field overall and outscored the Bucks by a 34-27 margin in the fourth quarter. They also maximized their free-throw opportunities, draining 19 of their 20 attempts from the charity stripe on the afternoon.

Harrison Barnes led the way for the visitors with 31 points, two rebounds and one steal. Dirk Nowitzki and J.J. Barea followed with matching 17-point efforts from the starting five and second unit, respectively. Nowitzki added five rebounds, one assist and one block while Barea supplemented his scoring with six assists and two rebounds. Yogi Ferrell produced 13 points, five assists, four rebounds and one steal. Wesley Matthews compiled eight points, six assists and one rebound as a complementary offensive presence.

All five members of the Bucks first unit hit double digits in the scoring column, beginning with Giannis Antetokunumpo, who totaled a near triple-double consisting of 31 points, 15 rebounds, nine assists, four steals and two blocks. Matthew Dellavedova provided 14 points, six assists and one steal in another start for Malcolm Brogdon (back). Khris Middleton tallied 13 points, five rebounds, four assists and one steal. Tony Snell poured in 12 points and added a rebound, an assist and a steal. Thon Maker supplied 11 points and one rebound. Jason Terry and Greg Monroe led the bench with modest six-point efforts.

The Mavericks next face the Sacramento Kings on the road Tuesday evening while the Bucks head to Oklahoma City for a Tuesday night showdown with the Thunder.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the Utah Jazz, 109-103, at AT&T Center on Sunday. 

Despite the fact that Utah took the opening lead in this game, that was all the success they'd have. In fact, San Antonio took the lead moments after that and never relinquished it from there in a near wire-to-wire win. The first and third quarters were decisive, with the Spurs outscoring the Jazz, 67-54. San Antonio's offense was extremely efficient, as they shot 52 percent from the field, 53 percent from three-point range and 86 percent from the free-throw line. A 42-36 rebounding differential was huge for San Antonio as well. In addition, the Spurs dominated the fastbreak scoring, winning that battle, 17-2.

The Jazz (47-30) had a tough task here against the Spurs and they simply didn't have enough to pull out an upset win. Rudy Gobert was Utah's best player, as he tallied 19 points, 14 rebounds, five assists and six blocks. Boris Diaw went a perfect 9-of-9 from the field to accrue 19 points, three rebounds and two assists against his former team. Gordon Hayward finished with 16 points, three rebounds and four assists. Joe Johnson and Shelvin Mack both scored 13 points a piece off the bench. On deck for Utah is a home matchup versus the Portland Trail Blazers on Tuesday. 

The Spurs (59-17) have now won 30 home games in six-straight seasons, as they continue to add to the record books. Kawhi Leonard once again led the way, as he accumulated 25 points, four rebounds, seven assists and two blocks. Tony Parker collected 21 points, four rebounds and five assists. Jonathan Simmons led all bench players with 17 points, while Pau Gasol provided 13 points and 12 rebounds of his own off the pine. San Antonio will look to keep rolling on Tuesday when they host the Memphis Grizzlies for their next game.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the host New Orleans Pelicans, 117-110, at Smoothie King Center on Sunday. 

These are two teams battling to get into the playoffs, as Chicago may have ended New Orleans season. It was a dominating win for the Bulls, as they led by at least six points for the final 30 minutes and took a 16-point lead into the half, while pulling out a wire-to-wire win. Shooting was key, as Chicago hit 49 percent of their shots, while holding New Orleans to just 41 percent from the field. Rebounding was huge as well, with Chicago winning that battle, 49-40. New Orleans couldn't slow down Chicago in transition either, as they allowed the Bulls to score 32 fastbreak points, while scoring just 12 on their end.

The Bulls (38-39) recently snuck into the seven-seed in the east, as this marks their fourth-straight win. Jimmy Butler was the player of the game, as he collected 39 points, six rebounds and five assists. Bobby Portis was huge off the bench, providing 21 points and 11 rebounds. Rajon Rondo was the only other starter in double figures, as he accumulated 10 points, nine rebounds, nine assists and three steals. Chicago will look to keep rolling on Tuesday in a road matchup versus the New York Knicks. 

The Pelicans (33-44) are now five games out of the final playoff spot in the west, as this was likely the nail in the coffin for their season. Anthony Davis led the way for New Orleans, as he totaled 30 points, 11 rebounds and three steals. DeMarcus Cousins finished with 26 points, 18 rebounds and three assists. Jrue Holiday accrued 17 points and six assists. Jordan Crawford was the only bench player in double figures, as he dropped 15 points off the Pelicans pine. New Orleans will host the Denver Nuggets for their next game on Tuesday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 113-105, at Air Canada Center on Sunday. 

Toronto were expected to win this game easily and they did just that in this eight-point win. In fact, Toronto actually rested many of their starters for the entire fourth quarter, as they led by at least six points for the final 15 minutes. The second quarter is where the Raptors separated themselves, as they outscored the Sixers, 31-20. Shooting was the difference in the game, with Toronto shooting 54 percent and Philadelphia hitting just 45 percent of their shots. The Raptors also took care of the interior, outscoring the Sixers, 58-42, in the paint. 

The Sixers (28-49) have now lost six of their last eight games, as they continue to limp to the finish line. Timothe Luwawu-Cabbarot led Philly, as he tallied 23 points and three rebounds. T.J. McConnell accrued four points, six rebounds and 11 assists. Dario Saric amassed 16 points and three rebounds. Nik Stauskas was a nice spark off the bench, producing 14 points and four assists. On deck for Philly is a home matchup versus the Brooklyn Nets on Tuesday,

The Raptors (47-30) are 8-1 across their last nine games, with the one-seed in the east now being in reach. Serge Ibaka had one of his best games in a Raptors uniform, collecting 24 points, six rebounds and six blocks on 11-of-17 shooting. DeMar DeRozan finished with 17 points and nine assists. Cory Joseph got another start and provided nine points, five rebounds and six assists. Jonas Valanciunas totaled 14 points, eight rebounds and two steals on 7-of-9 from the field. Delon Wright had a nice game off the bench, accumulating four points, five assists and four steals. Toronto will look to keep rolling on Tuesday in a road matchup against the Indiana Pacers.

The host Brooklyn Nets took down the Atlanta Hawks, 91-85, on Sunday.

Brooklyn (18-59) has actually won five games in its last eight contests despite being virtually guaranteed to finish with the league's worst record.  It was center Brook Lopez who sparked the win for Brooklyn on Sunday, as he scored 29 of the team's 91 points on the night.  Only three players scored in double figures for the Nets, as it was defense that helped them earn the win in the end.  Lopez also anchored the team on that end, blocking five shots and coming away with two steals.  

Atlanta (39-38) has been sliding badly in the standings, only worsening its situation by losing its ninth game in the last 11 outings on Sunday.  The team performed quite poorly on the offensive end, shooting just 37 points on the night and canning only seven three-pointers.  Big man Paul Millsap, who has missed the last three weeks with a knee injury, finally returned on Sunday.  He came off the bench, scoring 14 points but shooting only 4-of-14 and coming down with just four rebounds.  The team also struggled with turnovers, coughing the ball up 19 times on the night.  

The Nets will visit Philadelphia on Tuesday, while the Hawks will host the Celtics on Thursday.

The visiting Denver Nuggets brought down another playoff hungry team, the Miami Heat, on Sunday, 116-113.

Denver (36-40) now sits only two games out of the playoffs thanks to the win on Sunday.  Sophomore big man Nikola Jokic helped the team take down Miami, as he had 19 points to go along with a team-high 10 rebounds and seven assists.  Despite only hitting five three-pointers, the Nuggets had an excellent offensive night, as the team shot almost 51 percent from the field and dished out 25 team assists.  Forward Danilo Gallinari also had a big night, scoring a team-high 29 points and coming down with five rebounds.

Miami (37-40) is fighting for a playoff spot and is now 5-6 in its last 10 matchups.  The team had a strong night on the offensive end, shooting almost 49 percent and sinking 13 three-pointers on the night.  The Heat also dished out 26 assists on the night.  Five players scored in double-digits on the night, and point guard Goran Dragic led the team with 22 points.  However, the team finished out the night with a loss and trailed for most of the night.  

The Nuggets will visit New Orleans on Tuesday, while the Heat will visit Charlotte on Wednesday.

The host Cleveland Cavaliers beat the Indiana Pacers on Sunday, 135-130, in double overtime.

Cleveland (49-27) walked away with the win after what was an incredibly contested game.  The Cavs almost lost the lead with 2.1 seconds remaining in the first overtime period, as a foul by Tristan Thompson sent Indiana superstar Paul George to the free-throw line with Cleveland up only one.  Fortunately for the Cavaliers, George missed the first free-throw despite being among the league's most reliable at the line (he ranks third in the NBA in free-throw percentage this season).  The three-point shot proved to be Cleveland's best friend as they sought the much-needed win.  The Cavs hit 18 three-pointers, including two from sharpshooter J.R. Smith in the overtime periods that helped seal the deal for Cleveland.  Much of the win was also attributable to four-time MVP LeBron James, who had his 53rd career triple-double and a team-high 41 points.  The Cavs remain within half a game of first place thanks to the win.

Indiana (37-40) fought hard on Sunday but has still lost four straight games after the Cavs ended up victorious.  The loss came despite a season-high 43 points from star forward Paul George.  George added nine assists and nine rebounds while dueling with Cleveland's LeBron James.  The team also relied heavily on the three-point shot, hitting 16 threes on the night, just one shy of their season-high.  One of the team's issues was rebounding, as the Cavaliers held a 10-rebound edge over the Pacers on the night.  However, the Pacers did manage to find extra possessions with excellent ball management.  The team had only nine turnovers despite two overtime periods.

On Tuesday, the Cavaliers will host the Magic, while the Pacers will host the Raptors.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the Washington Wizards 139-115 at Oracle Arena on Sunday. 

The Warriors (63-14) grabbed their 11th straight win and had Stephen Curry on fire with 42 points on 15-of-22 shooting including nine three pointers. Curry also surpassed the 300 three-pointers made mark for the second straight season, although he is below his other worldly 402 three's he made in 2015-2016. The reigning MVP added eight assists, one rebound and one steal in the blow out victory. Klay Thompson added 23 points on 9-of-20 shooting, while Draymond Green pitched in a triple-double with 11 points, 13 assists and 12 rebounds. Golden State had the benefit of their bench, which ran seven players deep. Matt Barnes, Andre Iguodala and Shaun Livingston all saw 20-plus minutes of action, with Livingston being the most efficient amongst them as he finished with 17 points and seven rebounds on 8-of-10 shooting.

The Wizards (46-31) have been strong in the second half of the season and turned around their road woes, however, the Warriors high pace offense and Curry's ability to score three-pointers at will proved to much to handle. The loss puts them behind the Raptors for the 3-seed in the Eastern Conference, and the Raptors also hold the tiebreaker on the season. John Wall finished with 15 points and 11 assists, while Bradley Beal scored 20 points on 8-of-15 shooting. Bojan Bogdanovic was a bright spot off the bench once the rout was on, and contributed 20 points and six rebounds across 29 minutes of action. 

Both teams play on Tuesday, as the Warriors host the Minnesota Timberwolves, while the Wizards host the Charlotte Hornets.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Phoenix Suns 123-116 at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Sunday. 

The Rockets (52-25) had James Harden sidelined with the flu, which worked favorably into their schedule given the last placed Western Conference team, the Suns (22-56) were the opponent. The win also made it a 4-0 season sweep for Houston, and they got the job done with Patrick Beverley, Eric Gordon and Lou Williams. The three guards rotated in the backcourt and all scored 20-plus points while also logging 30-plus minutes each. Aside from the second quarter, where the Suns outscored the Rockets 33-28, Houston had some trouble staving off Phoenix comeback attempts, but nothing they weren't able to handle down the stretch. 

Beverley led the way with 26 points, nine assists and three rebounds on 11-of-19 shooting, while Gordon finished with 22 points, five assists, six boards, three blocks and one steal across 37 minutes. Troy Williams drew the start at small forward, and also found his way to 20-plus points after he finished with 21 points, three dimes and five rebounds on 7-of-12 shooting. Williams pitched in 23 points off the bench, while Clint Capela was strong on the glass in the starting rotation and contributed eight points and 12 rebounds. 

Tyler Ulis had a career night with 34 points on 15-of-22 shooting for the Suns, and the small rookie guard played big across the box score after he added nine assists and nine rebounds in a whopping 45 minutes. Devin Booker found his shooting rhythm late, but finished with 27 points, nine assists and five rebounds. 

Both teams play on Wednesday, as the Suns host the Golden State Warriors, while the Rockets host the Denver Nuggets.

The Los Angeles Clippers beat the Los Angeles Lakers, 115-104, at Staples Center on Saturday afternoon.

The Clippers (47-31) checked into Saturday's contest riding a winning wave that had seen them notch victories in six of the previous eight contests. Linchpins Blake Griffin and Chris Paul have been especially proficient as of late, and that pattern would repeat itself again Saturday. The dynamic duo combined for 65 points on outstanding 21-of-29 shooting, and Los Angeles tallied a 55.1 percent success rate from the field overall. The Lakers (21-55) hung tough, however, trailing only 55-50 at the half. However, the Clippers came out of halftime on a mission to put some distance between them and their in-town rivals and accomplished the feat by hanging 38 points on them in the third period. That helped build a 21-point lead heading into the final 12 minutes, one that the Lakers made some, but not enough, inroads against.

Promising prospect David Nwaba actually led the Lakers on the day with 19 points, six rebounds, one assist and two steals in 35 minutes off the bench. Brandon Ingram paced the starting five with 18 points, five boards, three assists, one steal and one block in his return from a three-game absence due to a knee injury. Thomas Robinson, seeing extended action as part of the trickle-down effect of Ivica Zubac's season-ending ankle injury, managed 16 points, nine boards, three assists and one steal. Julius Randle totaled 14 points, six rebounds, two assists and one steal. Larry Nance, Jr. drew the start and supplied eight points, four rebounds, three assists and two steals. 

Griffin led the way with 36 points, eight boards, five assists and one steal. Paul was right behind with 29 points, 12 assists, four boards and one steal.  J.J. Redick poured in 19 points and added five boards, two assists and one steal. DeAndre Jordan posted an 11-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included an assist, three steals and two blocks. 

The Lakers remain at Staples Center to tangle with the Memphis Grizzlies on Sunday afternoon and the Clippers also have a home date in their next contest, which is Wednesday night versus the Dallas Mavericks.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 106-104, at United Center on Saturday. 

In a battle between two teams trying to achieve a playoff berth, they left it all on the line in this close-fought battle. While there were only nine ties and nine lead changes in total, neither team led by more than 10 points. Jimmy Butler was the hero, as he hit two free-throws with two seconds left to take the lead and eventually win the game. Shooting was key for Chicago, as they hit 47 percent of their shots, while holding Atlanta to just 44 percent. The Bulls were also perfect from the free-throw line, as they went 14-of-14, with the Hawks hitting 13-of-17. 

The Hawks (39-37) have now lost eight of their last 10 games, as they're backpedaling their way into the postseason. Dennis Schroder led the way for Atlanta, as he tallied 29 points, seven rebounds and six assists on 12-of-19 shooting. Tim Hardaway Jr. finished second on the team, totaling 20 points, five rebounds and five assists. Dwight Howard recorded a double-double, amassing 13 points, 12 rebounds and three assists. Ersan Ilyasova started for Paul Millsap and contributed 13 points, four rebounds and four assists. Atlanta will be in action again on Sunday, as they take on the Brooklyn Nets in New York. 

The Bulls (37-39) continue to battle for a playoff berth, as this marks their third-straight victory. Butler not only hit the game-winning free-throws, he led the team with 33 points, five rebounds and eight assists. Rajon Rondo was equally as valuable, collecting 25 points, 11 rebounds, six assists and three steals. Nikola Mirotic accrued eight points, nine rebounds, five assists and two steals. Denzel Valentine led the bench with 13 points and two rebounds. On deck for Chicago is a road matchup against the New Orleans Pelicans on Sunday.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Orlando Magic, 121-111, at Barclay's Center on Saturday. 

In a battle between two teams fighting for nothing more than ping pong balls, both teams played a hard-fought game. In fact, there were seven ties and 10 lead changes in total, with neither team leading by more than 13 points. The second and fourth quarters are when Brooklyn made their money, outscoring Orlando, 59-42. The Nets ended up shooting 53 percent from the field, while holding the Magic to just under 50 percent. The glaring difference was down low, with Brooklyn outscoring Orlando, 72-32, in the paint. The Nets bench also dominated the Magic's bench, outscoring them, 72-16.

The Magic (27-50) have now lost nine of their last 12 games, with this defeat against the Nets showing just how bad they're struggling right now. Nikola Vucevic led Orlando, as he tallied 27 points and 11 rebounds on 13-of-20 from the field. Elfrid Payton accumulated 20 points, 11 rebounds and 11 assists en route to a triple-double. Aaron Gordon totaled 22 points, 15 rebounds and five assists. Evan Fournier scored 20 points to add to his two steals. Orlando is off until Tuesday, when they face the Cleveland Cavaliers on the road for their next game. 

The Nets (17-59) have now won four of their last seven games, which is one of the best stretches of the year. Brook Lopez led the way for Brooklyn, as he accrued 30 points, seven rebounds and two blocks. The other four starters combined for just 19 points and 15 rebounds. Jeremy Lin collected eight points, four rebounds, eight assists and two steals. Trevor Booker was huge off the bench, providing 23 points and eight rebounds on 11-of-12 shooting. Sean Kilpatrick also played well off the bench, dropping 15 points, five rebounds and four assists. Brooklyn will look to keep rolling on Sunday in a home matchup versus the Atlanta Hawks.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the host Minnesota Timberwolves, 123-117, on Saturday evening at Target Center. 

The Timberwolves led 31-18 after the first quarter, but the Kings woke up in the second, cutting the deficit to five heading to halftime. Sacramento pulled ahead by five after a strong third quarter and then matched the T-Wolves for 32 points each in a high-scoring fourth quarter. This was a solid win for the Kings (30-47) on the second night of a back-to-back, while it marks the 12th straight game that the Timberwolves (30-45) have given up at least 100 points. 

The Kings shot 56.4 percent from the field, as Buddy Hield led the way with 22 points on 9-of-15 shooting, in 34 minutes. Ty Lawson came up huge with 21 points and 11 assists, in 25 minutes off the bench. Lawson shot 5-of-8 from the field and 11-of-14 from the foul line. Langston Galloway chipped in 17 points off the bench, while Arron Afflalo added 16, to help round out a good team win. The Kings next contest comes on Tuesday, when they play host to the Mavericks. 

Meanwhile, Andrew Wiggins was the high-point man for Minnesota, with 32 points on 13-of-20 shooting, in 39 minutes. Karl-Anthony Towns followed up with 26 points and 11 rebounds, in 40 minutes. Ricky Rubio shot only 1-of-10 from the field, but managed to score a double-double with 11 points and 13 assists. Brandon Rush and Gorgui Dieng chipped in 11 points each. The Timberwolves will look to bounce back on Monday, when they play host to the Trail Blazers.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the visiting Phoenix Suns, 130-117, at Moda Center on Saturday evening. 

The Trail Blazers came out strong, earning a 16-point advantage after the first quarter, which turned out to be enough of a cushion for them to cruise to victory, even though they were out-scored 96-91 the rest of the way. This marks Portland's (38-38) sixth straight win and the 11th straight loss for the Suns (22-55). 

Damian Lillard led the way for Portland, with 31 points, while C.J. McCollum followed up with 29. Four other players score din double digits for the Trial Blazers, including Noah Vonleh, who finished with 12 points and 13 rebounds, in 35 minutes. Evan Turner chipped in 18 points on 6-of-11 shooting, in 26 minutes off the bench, while Al Farouq Aminu added 12 points, six rebounds and three steals, off the bench. The Trail Blazers shot 40.5 percent from long range, dished 21 assists and nabbed 12 steals to help earn the win. This win puts them 2.5 games ahead of the ninth-place Nuggets in the West. The Blazers will look for their seventh straight win, as they visit Minnesota to take on the Timberwolves on Monday. 

Meanwhile, Devin Booker was the high-point man for Phoenix, with 31 points on 10-of-25 shooting, in 42 minutes. Phoenix's four other starters scored in double digits, including T.J. Warren, who finished with 25 points on 10-of-17 shooting, in 43 minutes. Marquese Chriss added 19 points and 13 rebounds, for the solid double-double, while Alex Len tallied 12 points and seven rebounds, in only 16 minutes. The Suns will face the second game of a back-to-back, as they play host to the Rockets on Sunday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Indiana Pacers, 111-100, at Air Canada Centre on Friday evening.

The Raptors (46-30) were looking to bounce back from a tough 110-106 loss to the Hornets on Wednesday night, and they relied on two of their most dependable stars to get back into the win column. DeMar DeRozan continued to carry the Toronto offense on his shoulders by pouring in a game-high 40 points that he supplemented with nine rebounds, four assists and one steal. The All-Star guard made a whopping 20 visits to the charity stripe, draining 15 of those shots. Meanwhile, Jonas Valanciunas dominated down low against a Pacers (37-39) defense that's struggled against bigs all season. The Raptors won the rebounding battle overall by a 53-42 margin and also shot 45.1 percent from the field and 51.9 percent from behind the arc. The third quarter was key, as Toronto outscored Indiana, 34-20, to build sufficient cushion for the double-digit victory.

Paul George led the way for the visitors with 28 points, nine rebounds, three assists and one steal. Jeff Teague followed with 19 points, five assists, four rebounds and one steal. Thaddeus Young posted a near double-double with 12 points, eight rebounds and two assists. Myles Turner turned in nine points, nine boards, two assists, four blocks and one steal. C.J. Miles paced the bench with 15 points, three rebounds and one steal. Aaron Brooks was productive as a reserve as well with 11 points, three boards and two assists. 

Valanciunas supplied a 16-point, 17-rebound double-double that also included one assist, two blocks and one steal. Serge Ibaka managed 15 points, 12 boards, two assists and two blocks. DeMarre Carroll registered 12 points, four assists, one rebound and one block. Delon Wright led the second unit with 11 points, six assists and two rebounds. 

The Pacers next head to Cleveland to take on the Cavaliers on Sunday evening, while the Raptors remain home to take on the Philadelphia 76ers on that same evening.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the Denver Nuggets, 122-114, at Spectrum Center on Friday. 

In a battle between two teams fighting to get into the playoffs, the Hornets were able to ride a huge fourth quarter to a win. In fact, Charlotte outscored Denver, 36-20, in the fourth quarter to pull out the comeback victory. Defense was key for the Hornets, as they recorded 10 steals and 11 blocks, while winning the turnover differential, 13-6. Another key for Charlotte was the free-throw shooting, as they went 25-of-30 from the charity stripe, while Denver went just 8-of-11. Bench production really boosted the Hornets as well, outscoring the Nuggets bench, 50-19.

The Nuggets (35-40) have now lost three-straight games, as they find themselves two games out of the eight-seed in the west. Nikola Jokic did record his sixth triple-double in the defeat though, as he collected 26 points, 13 rebounds and 10 assists on 11-of-16 shooting. Gary Harris finished second on the team, totaling 20 points, five rebounds and three assists. Kenneth Faried got a rare start and provided 18 points and 13 rebounds. Danilo Gallinari tallied 19 points, five rebounds and four assists. Jameer Nelson put in 12 points and nine assists before departing with a calf injury in the third quarter. 

The Hornets (35-41) are now just two games behind the Indiana Pacers for the eight-seed in the east, as this win was crucial for that pursuit. Kemba Walker was the player of the game, as he accumulated 31 points, three rebounds and eight assists. Nicolas Batum amassed 13 points, five rebounds and nine assists. Marvin Williams, Cody Zeller and Michael Kidd-Gilchrist led the defense by combining for 24 rebounds, seven steals and eight blocks as the starting frontcourt. Frank Kaminsky was a huge spark off the bench, dropping 22 points in 27 minutes. 

Both teams travel on Sunday for their next game, with Denver playing the Miami Heat and Charlotte facing the Oklahoma City Thunder.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 122-105, at Quicken Loans Arena on Friday evening.

The Cavaliers (48-27) checked into Friday's contest in serious need for a victory, as they'd dropped four out of five and actually found themselves displaced from their customary top perch in the Eastern Conference. Cleveland knew they'd have to be wary of a considerably improved Philadelphia squad that had already played them tough in two prior games this season. The first quarter was more of the same, as the hosts emerged with a razor-thin 32-29 edge. However, LeBron James and company turned on the after-burners over the middle periods, outscoring the Sixers by a 72-48 margin over the second and third periods. The Cavs saw four members of the first unit post double digits in the scoring column and they shot a stellar 52.6 percent from the field and 44.8 percent from three-point range. They also prevailed in the rebounding battle, 49-42.

Richaun Holmes and Timothe Luwawu-Cabarrot co-led the Sixers (28-48) with matching 19-point efforts, with the former adding seven rebounds, two assists and two steals and the latter supplying four rebounds and one steal. With Robert Covington (knee) now out for the season, Justin Anderson celebrated his new permanent starter role with a 12-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three assists and a block. T.J. McConnell tallied 10 points, seven assists, three rebounds and two steals. Dario Saric had a down game by his standards with eight points, four rebounds and four assists, but Shawn Long helped make for it with 16 points, four rebounds, one steal and one block off the bench.

James paced the Cavs with a game-high 34 points, which he complemented with nine rebounds and six assists. Kyrie Irving followed with 24 points, nine assists, one rebound and two steals. Kevin Love posted an 18-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three assists and three steals. J.R. Smith was solid with 14 points, four rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Channing Frye led the bench with 12 points.

The Sixers head north of the border to take on the Toronto Raptors on Sunday evening, while the Cavs remain home and await the Indiana Pacers  on Sunday evening as well.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Orlando Magic, 117-116, at TD Garden on Friday. 

Boston were expected to win this game easily, but Orlando gave them a hard-fought battle. In fact, there were 11 ties and 18 lead changes in this thriller. Despite the Celtics taking 14 less shots than the Magic, they ended up shooting 45 percent from the field, with Orlando shot just 40 percent. The Magic actually won many of the statistics, as they ended up leading in rebounding, assists, free-throw percentage, three-point percentage, points in the paint and turnovers in this defeat.

The Magic (27-49) have now lost eight of their last 11 games, as their defense continues to falter. Aaron Gordon led the way for Orlando, as he tallied 32 points, 16 rebounds and two blocks. Evan Fournier finished second on the team, totaling 20 points, two assists and two steals. Elfrid Payton fell just shy of a triple-double, collecting 12 points, nine rebounds, 15 assists and two steals. The Magic will be in action again on Saturday in a road matchup against the Brooklyn Nets. 

The Celtics (49-27) recently captured the top-spot in the east, as this close win may prove to be the difference at the end of the year. Isaiah Thomas was the player of the game, as he amassed 35 points, three rebounds and seven assists. Al Horford accumulated 12 points, nine rebounds and six assists. Jae Crowder accrued 18 points, five rebounds and two steals. On deck for Boston is a road matchup versus the New York Knicks on Sunday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Detroit Pistons in overtime, 108-105, at BMO Harris Bradley Center on Friday evening. 

The Bucks (40-36) allowed the Pistons (35-42) to climb back into the game after they'd ambushed by a 35-22 margin in the first quarter. Detroit came back to outscore their hosts, 51-36, over the second and third periods, and then led by as much as 91-81 after a Kentavious Caldwell-Pope three-pointer with 5:09 remaining. However, an 8-0 run by Milwaukee over the subsequent 2:11 closed the gap to 91-89 and a Thon Maker basket with 51 seconds left tied the game at 95, eventually leading to overtime. A see-saw extra period saw the game knotted the game at 102 with as little as 1:22 remaining, but Khris Middleton's 25-foot three-point jumper at the 40-second mark began a game-clinching 6-0 run for the Bucks. 

Detroit was led by Tobias Harris, who posted 23 points, seven rebounds, three assists and one steal off the bench. Caldwell-Pope followed with 17 points, eight boards, two assists and two steals. Ish Smith and Beno Udrih contributed matching 16-point efforts from the starting five and second unit, respectively, with the former adding five assists and four rebounds and the latter providing eight assists, one rebound and two steals. Maurice Morris supplied 13 points, four boards and three assists. Jon Leuer posted nine points and 10 rebounds, while Andre Drummond compiled seven points, 13 boards, two assists, two steals and two blocks. 

Giannis Antetokunumpo spearheaded the Bucks attack with 28 points, 14 rebounds, nine assists, two blocks and one steal. Middleton was right behind him with a 25-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included one assist and one steal. Maker exploded for a career-high 23 points, which he supplemented with two rebounds and one steal. Matthew Dellavedova drew the start for Malcolm Brogdon (back) and totaled six points, seven assists and three rebounds.

The Pistons are now off until next Wednesday evening, when they take on the Toronto Raptors at home. The Bucks remain home for a Sunday afternoon showdown with the Dallas Mavericks.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the Dallas Mavericks, 99-90, at FedEx Forum on Friday. 

Memphis were expected to win this game easily, but Dallas made a late run to make a respectable scoreline. It was a near wire-to-wire win for the Grizzlies, as Dallas' only lead came in the first quarter, with it being a one-point lead for less than a minute. The second quarter was the difference, with Memphis winning that quarter, 34-15. Rebounding was a big factor for the Grizzlies, as they won that battle, 47-38. Dallas couldn't get anything going on offense either, shooting 38 percent from the field and 35 percent from three-point range.

The Mavericks (31-44) playoff hopes have been steadily slipping away and this loss may be the nail in the coffin. Despite shooting just 3-of-17 from the field, Dirk Nowitzki led Dallas with 13 points and 12 rebounds. Wesley Matthews matched those 13 points, adding three rebounds and seven assist to his tally. J.J. Barea led the bench, as he provided 13 points and five assists. 

The Grizzlies (42-34) have now followed up two wins after four-straight losses, as they appear to be out of that slump. Mike Conley was the star, as he collected 28 points, five rebounds and six assists. No other starter had more than nine points. Zach Randolph finished second on the team, providing 22 points, 12 rebounds and three assists off the bench. Troy Daniels also played well off the bench, dropping 21 points. Vince Carter went just 1-of-7 from the field, but still accrued three points, eight rebounds and five assists. 

Both teams play again on Sunday, with Memphis traveling to play the Los Angeles Lakers and Dallas playing the Milwaukee Bucks on the road,

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the Sacramento Kings, 117-89, at Smoothie King Center on Friday. 

This was a revenge game for many players, but the Pelicans made minced meat of the Kings. It was as dominating as it could be, with New Orleans holding a double-digit lead for the final three quarters. Defense was key, as the Kings were held to 39 percent shooting, while committing 22 turnovers. New Orleans ended up shooting 48 percent, while committing just 12 turnovers. The 30 combined steals and blocks for the Pelicans marked a season-high as well. as they also dominated the points in the paint (60-38) and fastbreak differential (27-10).  

The Kings (29-47) had a tough task here playing against their former franchise player and they simply didn't have enough to compete in this matchup. Ben McLemore led the team in scoring off the bench, as he provided 15 points, eight rebounds and four steals. Willie Cauley-Stein recorded a double-double, amassing 11 points and 14 rebounds. Skal Labissiere accrued 13 points and eight rebounds. Buddy Hield produced 13 points, eight rebounds and three assists. On deck for Sacramento is a road matchup versus the Minnesota Timberwolves on Saturday.

The Pelicans (33-43) wanted to show up for their big trade deadline acquisition against his former team and they did just that in this dominating win. DeMarcus Cousins abused his former team, totaling 37 points, 13 rebounds, four assists, three steals and two blocks.
